Higgs boson in detail
Last summer, the report that scientists may have discovered the Higgs boson caused a real stir - and not without reason.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all particles in the universe, nothing more.
In addition, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the Standard Model — our best, or at least “least imperfect,” description of the nature and behavior of matter — but which has never been discovered before.
But physicists are not yet sure that we are talking about the Higgs boson.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we are dealing with a really new particle and that it strongly resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data presented this week at one major physical congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, although some data is not enough to be completely sure.
Let’s imagine that we are talking about the Higgs boson, since the chances of making a mistake seem minimal, and let’s see what it means.
There is, in this world, one law absolutely inevitable, which states that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to circumvent this rule, do not even try too hard, otherwise harm yourself.
But although particle physics is a rather strange world, it turns out that it also has one law of this nature: the Pauli exclusion principle, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" is, in general terms, in some of their characteristics.
On this basis, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find respectable citizens called fermions who are judiciously subject to the Pauli principle.
On the other hand, there are bosons, a nefarious gang of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least for this principle, which means that they can quietly find themselves in the same place at the same time.
According to the website (by the way, quite unusual) Particle Adventure Berkeley Lab, these bosons are divided into two groups: mesons, which we will not talk about here, and "particles of force", through which the main forces of nature and which in some way refers to the Higgs boson.
These very bosons, it should be emphasized, are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to one incredibly banal boson: a photon, or “particle of light”, which is the “courier” of electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a single particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it “disrupts” the electromagnetic field at that particular location, roughly like a rock thrown into a pond.
From this "disruption" is born electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and, therefore, one of the bosons of "power carriers".
A more stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the only difference that in order for this boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, must be "broken".
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; in order to excite it, it is necessary to achieve very, very high energies, as if it were a frozen pond, the surface of which could be shaken only by a very large stone.
That’s why a huge particle accelerator is needed, like the one operated at CERN — the Large Hadron Collider, which is a ring with a diameter of 27 km! — to achieve such huge energies.
The electromagnetic field analogy is also useful for explaining the relationship between the Higgs boson and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, while others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never hold on to the refrigerator itself.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have mass, while others (like a photon, by the way) do not.
So, what “could” all this research bring, Ms. Plamondon asks?
In science, they are used to test the correctness of the Standard Model (SM), and this also allows physicists to find a discrepancy between the results of observations and forecasts of SM.
In addition, some of them are eager for such a discrepancy to be revealed, because the slightest discrepancy can open the door for “new physics” and shut some Model holes.
The latter, I must say, still has significant drawbacks, offering no explanation for gravity (ow!), or for dark matter, which forms about 80% of the universe (ow!).
But so far, CERN has not found such discrepancies.
Consequences
The use of these studies for the daily life of the average person is more difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that it is not.
See: in the early 60s, pioneers of laser research in Bell laboratories could not even imagine what revolution their work would cause.
They anticipated their applications in science, but nothing more.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (previous ones were pulsed) in 1962, said that the laser was originally considered more like a “laboratory gadget”.
Imagine...
And in addition, the application can be found for the tools that accompany the study.
For example, the same Williard Boyle during his optical research in 1969 developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, although not its original purpose, now serves as the “eye” for all digital cameras in the world and earned the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Large Hadron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it only shows, in fact, that everything can be.
Palliative care is the best way to die...
Quebec’s Commission for Decent Death recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate is due to resume soon, and a bill is being drafted at this time.
However, much remains to be done in this critical area.
"Duty" tried to take a closer look.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Monteregi.
Prostate cancer, which destroyed him from the inside, gave him a delay of two years.
“I was given five years, I lived seven,” he says, between life and death, lying in bed at Victor-Gadboua palliative care shelter in Beloy, where he arrived the day before.
“But it’s always a shock, it’s impossible to prepare for it,” he says.
The disease does its job: an incredible weakness that does not allow you to go to the toilet on your own and even eat on your own.
Sitting at a table on which there is an appetizing lunch, he surrenders and agrees to be helped to eat.
He wakes up, even manages to smile, talk to strangers who work around him, bring him medicine, take him to the bath.
Courage before an ordinary death.
“My biggest wish to be cured of diarrhea is humiliating,” he admits.
A few hours later, the staff found a cure for this ailment.
“During life, we are taught that a man should urinate standing up,” says Pierre Broder, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadboua shelter.
Regression to the state of the child is an unbearable humiliation for some.
“It all depends on the ability of man” to come to terms with the decline, he says.
Since, according to many people involved in palliative care, important events happen in the midst of this decline.
Patients who enter the Victor-Gadboua palliative care facility are all cancer patients.
Forecasts give them a maximum of three months of life.
At this stage, the team of doctors and nurses does not provide any more care, called "therapeutic."
Mrs. A., 89, is most afraid of dying "in the mind from suffocation."
But the disease allowed me to get to know my children.
“I have good kids,” she adds.
“I don’t want anything else in life,” she says, before allowing her to put on a breathing mask.
She is still waiting in the coming days for the last visit of her son, who came from Italy.
In the shelter Victor-Gadbua with the help of a group of volunteers provide body care and nutrition assistance.
This is the palliative care that remains when nothing else can be done.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, for every 11,700 inhabitants, there is one place in palliative care.
That's not much, considering we're all gonna die sooner or later.
Here, life goes on in the best conditions possible, explains Dr. Christian Martel, one of the doctors of the shelter.
Whether it is physical, emotional or mental comfort.
To the dying person, we will agree to provide mouthwashes from brandy or pepsi, whatever he asks.
Diabetics are no longer forced to control their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we brought a beer to Mr. H., who died tonight.
In the morning, his son finished this beer in the legs of the deceased.
“We help loved ones as well as patients,” says Natalie Savar, director of nursing.
In the shelter of Victor Gadbua, no day is like the previous one.
Next to the 93-year-old, who enjoys his last meeting with his family in the yard, sitting on his pillows during a toast in his honor, tragically dies a young man 36 years old, surrounded by parents, wife and two young children and tried everything to survive.
“In the last six months, three to five beds are always occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45,” said Dr. Christian Martel.
53% of patients admitted to the Victor Gadbua Asylum come from home, and 47% from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is estimated that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care that is provided to alleviate the suffering of patients who have entered the final stage of their lives, whether at home, in a hospital or in a shelter.
And some institutions, such as the Victor Gadbois Asylum and the Greater Montreal Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in cancer care.
It is this large gap in Quebec’s health care system that makes many palliative care professionals wary of passing legislation legalizing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto signed by the luminaries in the field of palliative care, Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating and indicating their disagreement with such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christian Martel, Quebec's health care system is not effective enough to ensure the right to high-quality palliative care before the transition to euthanasia is allowed.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who spent 14 days in the emergency room in terrible pain, and no one took the necessary measures to alleviate them.
I am afraid that patients want to die only because they do not receive adequate care.
At the same time, many oncologists until the last day try to save patients, despite pessimistic forecasts.
Hopes for Helen Richard's survival were already minimal when she stopped exhausting chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was discontinuing treatment, she told me that she regretted that I was discontinuing the fight.
She told me that my days were numbered!
There is no all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask for death are grateful to the medical staff for not fulfilling their request, after the palliative care team eases their pain.
However, it should be noted that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the fight against pain.
According to Elsie Monroe, director of palliative care at the Greater Montreal Palliative Care Society, patients are not susceptible to pain relief in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, in which the patient sleeps until the moment of his death, either from time to time or constantly.
We can no longer pretend that we do not know about this suffering.
Increasingly, patients who fail to relieve pain will be able to have access to palliative sedation.
Patients suffering from pain always say the same phrase: "I want to die."
But it doesn’t necessarily mean “I want to be euthanized,” it means “I want to feel better.”
