Large-scale real estate scandals in Quebec
Road officials, construction contractors, political party fundraisers and Italian mafia specialists tell day after day what they know about the colossal “system” that envelops the construction industry, government officials, politicians, trade unionists and the mafia.
“Industry” has been very expensive for Quebec taxpayers, especially in 1990 and 2000.
"It is curious how this system crumbles after all the means have been put into action, jokes Jacques Duchenault, a deputy and former chief of police of Montreal."
It was thanks to him that the scandal broke out in 2011 as a by-product of the investigation of official crimes related to road construction contracts in Quebec, to which the Liberal Prime Minister of that time, Jean Charet, agreed very reluctantly.
The Duchenne Report established a direct link between industry, secret political party funding, and corruption.
“Since the start of the investigation in 2010, he stresses, the Department of Transportation alone would have saved a billion dollars on contracts,” if some held back their instincts to take a stake.
The Charbonneau Commission "has already removed two mayors," he adds, hoping that it will be able to "open up the schemes behind the individuals."
Permanent Anti-Corruption Unit established in 2011
The case was joined by the Permanent Anti-Corruption Unit, established in 2011, which included an extensive staff of government auditors, investigators and analysts.
And, in addition, the employees of the special unit "Molot", which after 2009 forced the "sink cartel" of Montreal, to stop overstating the value of contracts.
A series of searches have been carried out in recent weeks, and some municipal officials, notably Frank Zampino and Richard Marcotte, the mayor of a small town, have been charged with fraud and corruption.
Next up is Gilles Wayancourt, who recently stepped down as mayor of Laval, Quebec’s third-largest city.
He is suspected of repeatedly receiving bribes when placing state orders.
In addition, several Montreal route engineers and construction contractors of Italian origin, including Tony Accurso and Lino Zambito, were formally charged.
The latter detonated a real bomb, telling the investigation about the “system” of obtaining state contracts.
For several years, Zambito gave 3% of the value of the contracts concluded in Montreal, to a certain intermediary associated with the mafia, who, in turn, transferred money to the party of Mayor Gerald Trumble “United Montreal”.
In the 2000s, Zambito made money to the right and left. He transferred more than 88,000 Canadian dollars (about 68,000 euros) to various parties in the province, mainly liberals who were then in power.
In addition, he admitted that he illegally raised funds for the former Deputy Prime Minister from the Liberal Party Natalie Normando.
Sewerage contracts in which the cost was inflated
In Montreal, the “system” of corruption worked flawlessly.
Gilles Surprenan, a former civil engineer, described it in detail before the commission: for ten years, he received from construction firms gifts, invitations to trips, golf tournaments, restaurants, hockey matches and bribes in total for $ 736,000 in exchange for sewer contracts, the cost of which he inflated.
Other officials responsible for road construction admitted that they received on the paw, inflating bills by 30-40% with fake additions.
Then one organizer from the mayor's party, Martin Dumont, accused Mr. Trumble of deliberately turning a blind eye to the existence of a parallel budget that filled the party's box office with dirty money.
Following these revelations, Mr. Trumble resigned in early November, plunging Montreal into a deep crisis.
Chantal Rulo was one of the first MPs in Montreal to sound the alarm.
The mayor of Riviera de Prairie County in the east of the island, she has been resisting since 2010 the sale of a municipal plot bought for $ 5 million and resold for $ 1.6 million to developers in the midst of a construction boom.
70% of dirty money in election campaigns
She says that in the investigation, which will eventually be launched, she "will pull a thread to understand the functioning of the system infested with ants to stop gangrene and identify the culprits."
This process is characterized as “painful, but positive”.
We are in the process of cleaning up the wound, but Montreal will need its own investigative team and an observer to avoid returning questionable practices.
How we clean up at home.
Regularly.
Jacques Duchenault notes that “officials stole hundreds of millions of dollars,” but he is particularly concerned about the role of “elective officials who knew about this scheme,” but did not participate in the fraud.
Given that the share of dirty money in the financing of the election campaign in Quebec reaches 70%, he jokes: “I was told that it was just a pale reflection of reality.”
The government of Quebec proposes to limit donations to parties to $ 100, but, according to him, this will not change the situation: "Until we strictly limit election spending, there will be dirty money in politics."
It calls for a complete overhaul of government contracting and party funding: “We can’t go lower; boldly looking into the heart of things, we can build a home on a stronger foundation, with better control and legitimacy.”
If this story casts a shadow on the international image of Quebec and Montreal, Mr. Duchenault calls on those who laugh to look into their own backyard.
