Pay and sell without the help of banks - with Bitcoin
The complete opposite of the current monetary exchange, based on central banks, numbered transactions between receiving parties with commission fees for their processing.
In addition, as often happens with these technologies, there is clearly a political vision: the belief that the current monetary system, consisting of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (nickname), is simultaneously a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros ...) and a secure exchange protocol like BitTorrent, which allows you to exchange files between participants of the same level.
About 200,000 transactions have already been recorded with 15,000 computers on the network.
Several thousand sites accept bitcoins for donations or as a means of payment.
The bitcoin exchange rate, peaking at $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, dropped to $2 five months later before returning to around $10 today (the rates are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing special compared to the global exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) in its report on virtual currency, published in October, was interested in this system.
He describes bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency,” “competing with the dollar or the euro,” and “similar to conventional currencies.”
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies, such as “credits” used to promote a video game that are earned during the game or that can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But exchange operations are always controlled and processed by some central authority.
In Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are simultaneously bookkeepers, auditors, currency issuers, buyers, and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses, similar to an email.
Only for each new payment, the user can choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically, using a double-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is possible to verify that the bitcoins used in the transaction do exist in a public ledger sent throughout the network.
The key step is to register a new transaction in this book.
It goes through solving a mathematical problem sent to computers, which, like a temporary central bank, gets the privilege of adding this new line.
We are talking about the phase of hashing a file, that is, converting a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers “take” a new transaction and add a number to it before “hashing” everything together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes easily check that it is correct.
The transaction thus turns out to be inextricably linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If, for the purpose of deception, the user very quickly (in less than ten minutes) wished to pay twice with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed, since they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solved the problem receives 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the award is regularly split in half, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to one hundred million, which leaves another reserve.
The complexity of the task also increases with increasing computing power.
Network life has already experienced ups and downs.
Bitcoin sites have been attacked and bitcoins have been stolen from reserves.
“The defect used does not concern the protocol itself,” said Pierre Noiza, who recently launched Paymium, a company that makes payments in real money using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reported the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this disadvantage.
Major players such as Wikipedia refuse to accept donations of this kind.
Others, such as the WordPress blog platform, allow them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and found that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
"Giant sales" were announced in November.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmqvist, who works at Coinabul, which converts bitcoin to gold.
Pierre Noiza, another author of the manual on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as an operating network.
Its system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (in real money) or contactless payment via a mobile phone, but it uses Bitcoin to verify transactions, which thus comes out cheaper.
The owner has better control over their personal data and can thus be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for entrepreneurs who do not need to install new devices or software.
It is enough to provide an address that can be “photographed and recognized” by the phone, Pierre Noiza clarifies, assuring that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general tendency to revise hierarchical systems in favor of more horizontal ones.
“Before Bitcoin is approved, it will take some time, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
The ECB in its report suggests, by the way, to reconsider the various risks that are considered to be increased today, if this system succeeds.
