Heavy Births of the Egyptian Constitution
This is President Mohamed Morsi’s new risky move.
While Egypt is divided more than ever, on the issue of a constitutional declaration that temporarily gives him emergency powers, he has decided to play all-in.
After taking everyone by surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on the final text the next day.
Exactly one week ago, the head of state gave the Assembly two additional months to complete the work.
Soon, for two years, Egypt has relied on a preliminary text that has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal contradictions.
This new initiative only increased the division of the country.
According to his opponents, the President persists in his “autocratic delirium”, continuing to “violate the word” and “violate the law”.
In the camp, his followers believe that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis, accelerating the transition process.
The referendum must be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time, which forces the Brothers to abandon the intention to explain to the Egyptians the text, article by article.
For the president, it is also a way to restore public and democratic legitimacy, while discontent rages across the country.
Mohamed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote positively, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Moreover, the call for an accelerated vote is like an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: “Either you vote for my text, or I reserve extraordinary powers,” which are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
In this strange atmosphere, 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamists, voted yesterday for the text.
Most liberals did not respond to the challenge.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they slammed the door, feeling unable to deliver their opinion.
Representatives of human rights defenders, religious minorities or civil society did the same.
To reach the required quorum, 11 alternate participants were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, in most cases, the articles were voted unanimously.
Commentators, by the way, were amused by the fact that one of the few disagreements of the day arose around ... a time for prayer, since some members of the committee felt that the hours of the Constituent Assembly were misconfigured.
The text on which yesterday was still voting consists of 234 articles.
The object of general attention, article 2 eventually remained identical to the article from the 1971 Constitution stating that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the main requirements, hoped to replace the “principles” with “rules”, which would enable their stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a testament to their goodwill and respect for other members of Egyptian society.
“Hypocrisy,” say the liberals, who see it as PR.
Because, in their opinion, the Islamization of the Constitution occurs through other articles.
They point in particular to article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to the verification of compliance with sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pomier, this is alarming, because “people called to make decisions are not elected and do not have any democratic legitimacy.”
We can see the rise of theocracy.”
Many liberals, moreover, are excited by the fact that the next rector of this university seems to be much less moderate than the current one.
“There is no specific religious intervention at the moment.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of civil law.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulema, but people with a university education, some have studied in the French system,” says Alexis Bloye, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he admits that “there may be ambiguity around Article 220, as the terms used in it are borrowed from religious vocabulary.
This applies in particular to "fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, - ed.].
And in the future, there may be a question as to how competent the civilian judges are to rule on this.”
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is criticized because it gives broad powers to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood claims that they have significantly decreased in comparison with what they were under the old regime.
Another controversial point: the authority of the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the consideration of the defense budget will be held not in Parliament, but in the National Defense Council.
Nor will the trial of civilians in military courts be prohibited, despite requests from human rights associations.
The latter also expressed concern about the text, which they consider detrimental to freedom.
Blasphemy has been maintained and insults are now prohibited, which can have serious consequences for freedom of speech, and especially for freedom of the press.
In addition, none of the articles speak anymore about protecting women, emphasizes Heba Moraef, of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture in article 36.
A word that did not appear in the previous Constitution.
