- It definitely can not be called a panacea - the question of privacy arises, because you do not always want to inform others about your actions and intentions.
In fact, all kinds of interactions with computers are good, but each in its own niche.
For example, to control devices in public places, we had a project in which we thought about gestures, but not over sweeping, but over such meager, short ones.
At the same time, the gestures were removed not by the camera of the device, but by a wrist bracelet that recorded the movements of bones and muscles.
While it is large, but theoretically it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But in general, the future is a mixed type of management, for example, gesture + voice.
- How's that?
- Like, how do you ask me to give you this soda jar?
You can say it and show it at the same time.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, it's going to be very hard to recognize.
- So you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or can not at the moment?
- Not necessarily, but it's a mutual encounter.
I think that in the near future we will mainly have to work on developing new types of sensors that will allow us to more accurately determine human reactions.
It can be, for example, laser sensors, they give a good resolution in depth, this is very important.
- If we talk about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your claims to modern cameras?
Lack of resolution, depth, or something else?
- In principle, the current generation is something from which you can start in our work on three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be good to get megapixels 8 at a speed of 1000 k/s.
