Shimon Ornest: At concerts we want to accumulate positive energy
What do you think about the end of the world in less than a month?
This is just one of the many disturbing news that we humans get so easily.
Together with the band The Tap Tap, we joke about it all the time and say that we are the only band in the world that can gather enough positive energy to delay or prevent the end of the world.
Moreover, in December you are going to give absolutely unique three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you tell readers more about this?
We are talking about a national fundraising event, which we have been planning for two years.
We decided to take advantage of the marketing potential that the Mayan calendar has, the end of which is announced on December 21 at 11:10.
The day before this event, on December 20, at 21:00, three concerts in Prague, Brno and Ostrava will start in parallel.
They will end, roughly speaking, at the moment when the May calendar ends on the island of Kiribati in the Pacific Ocean, whose time zone is 12 hours earlier than ours.
Who came up with this idea?
Initially it was my idea, then we all came up with our artist Gonza Augusta.
In addition to the fact that we want to accumulate enough positive energy and prevent the end of the world, we also want to think with the public about the state of this world we will one day pass on to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the May calendar, we have created a unique collection of items from shoes, T-shirts, bags and original keys against the end of the world. These things can be bought on the website www.e-tap.cz and thus at the same time provide us with support.
The Tap Tap, along with other musicians, also performed the anthem against the end of the world, which is called "The End of the World Is Cancelled".
Will YouTube’s already beloved anthem be played at these benefit concerts?
Of course, at the very end, if in the end everything works out and the end of the world does not come.
It will be sung by all the performers at all concerts at the same time.
The anthems will also be broadcast live on Czech television.
The lyrics to this song were written and played the role of Jesus in the music video by Tomasz Ganak, also participating in the performance of Xindl X.
How did you start working with them?
We also cooperate with other people of Czech cultural life, as we hold many charity events and concerts.
We try to actively involve them in these projects.
It turned out that many people like to work with us, they are interested.
Where will the proceeds from the concert against the end of the world go?
For the purchase of equipment for the barrier-free educational center STUDEO, for the sixth year we have been working with the Tap civil association at the Edlichka Institute.
Teachers regularly visit the students of the schools of the Edlichka Institute and conduct fun and interesting events with them.
The students themselves do not have the means to go to the teachers, and we are trying in this way to provide them with this opportunity.
As part of the additional construction project of the Edlichka Institute, a separate building will appear in the future, in which we will move with this project.
Several musical groups and performers will perform at each concert.
What were the selection criteria?
We have tried to create a program that will be of interest to all generations, including children.
For example, in Prague, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Barta, The Tap Tap, Marian Bango and Jiri Suhi will perform.
All details can be found at www.kpks.cz.
Are you planning any such “grand events” in the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the Prague Spring festival and here, of course, we will prepare an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we’d love to do a show at the Czech National House in New York, and I personally, if we’re in the US, would love to do a show in Washington and Chicago.
About abroad you have serious plans, you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London and Moscow.
The Tap Tap is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you deal with the road in terms of organization and logistics?
It’s not as scary as it seems at first glance.
We have five participants on electric wheelchairs, their strollers must travel in the luggage compartment, plus a large number of cargo and tool boxes.
However, so far we have managed this without any problems. Czech Airlines and British Airways have always been excellently prepared for us, which surprised me so many times.
Even in Moscow, where we recently returned, everything went without problems.
Thanks to trips abroad, you can compare different countries in terms of accessibility, public attitudes towards people with disabilities, and so on.
What have you encountered so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other countries where everything functions better than we do, in Russia we have witnessed that in the east it is still at a basic level.
Compared to Prague in Moscow, there are many barriers, and here is still a curiosity about the independent movement of a person on an electric wheelchair in the city center.
Also, there are such banal things as giving way to a disabled person in an elevator.
Fortunately, there are already public organizations that try to draw people’s attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
What, on the contrary, do we constantly have to catch up with the advanced countries?
There are a lot of things that are far behind.
But it is important to clarify that improving and improving the situation always depends on the efforts of those concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is quite normal that people with severe disabilities move on the streets on their own, can go to the toilet, to the museum, and anywhere else.
It is not very common that a large number of people with disabilities take an active part in public life, in this we are a little ahead of them with The Tap Tap!
Respect for the public or barrier-free is one thing, but the moment famous athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers appear among us, then everything will really begin to change.
So far, these are isolated cases - people with a strong will.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but back to two years ago, what made you organize it in 1998?
I entered the Edlichka Institute as a teacher, there were many young people around me who wanted to do something.
And since I am a musician and play saxophone, then together with a colleague I organized an interesting musical circle.
Well, over time, as our presenter Ladya Angelovich says, it got a little out of control (laughs).
Has it only been popular in recent years, or am I confused about something?
It’s true, it helped us that we began to join the famous singers and actively work on the promotion of the group.
We came to the conclusion that the work that no one can appreciate, in fact, as if does not exist.
Thanks to the funds of the European Union, we can afford qualified teachers, equipment and so on.
Did you have a goal to promote The Tap Tap so well?
From the very beginning, I felt their potential in the ability to do something extraordinary.
Show business is full of things that imitate each other.
This is logical, everything new is taken with caution, and it lasts for a long time.
There are very few rare things, but I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression of a person who sees us, of course, is pity, it is natural.
But this pity is completely superfluous, because people with disabilities are not some suffering and all the abandoned personalities that we should feel sorry for.
They are people who can live a full life and develop, of course, only if they have the necessary resources.
I say that if people with disabilities succeed, it is a shift not only for them, but for the whole society.
Did success come from being the tough boss that many people think you are?
If we want to do quality work, we have to be uncompromising in many things and keep a certain discipline.
But I think that's normal.
Some people come to us with a romantic performance and fly in the clouds, and when they learn that twice a week they have to go to rehearsals, attend preparatory courses and spend a lot of time on the road, very quickly lose enthusiasm.
But this happens in any group that wants to work and achieve something.
There are currently 20 members of The Tap Tap.
How many were there at the beginning of 1998?
There's only one Ladja Angelovic.
We are an open group, people come and go, it is impossible to prevent.
For those who have will and willpower, our doors are always open.
