Operation Argo: When there is nowhere worse, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of Islamist student demonstrators seized the U.S. embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the deposed Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi, who fled after the U.S. revolution, who had been the patron of his regime for decades.
For the US administration, the positive outcome of the situation was not intended - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, because it could fundamentally undermine the confidence of allies in other countries.
However, to achieve the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, she was not able.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later amplified by an unsuccessful attempt to free the hostages by force.
The prisoners were finally released after 444 days, after negotiations mediated by the Algerian government.
Their fate caused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment at home.
The defeat in Iran contributed greatly to Jimmy Carter's defeat in the 1980 presidential election, culminating in the election of Ronald Reagan.
The film, directed by actor Ben Affleck “Operation Argo” describes one of the episodes of the story that brought America small victories.
Shortly before the occupation of the embassy, six workers managed to escape.
After a difficult turn, they finished their journey at the residence of the Canadian Embassy.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to remove them from Iran, with the help of an extravagant cover-up legend, according to which they went on Canadian passports as members of the film crew who were looking for a place in the country for filming a sci-fi epic.
Combination of genres
The plan, which was invented by evacuation expert Tony Mendes, required Hollywood to cooperate.
In order for the legend to be reliable, specialized magazines wrote about the project of the film, held press conferences, the fictional production company had a real office.
Details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film is based on the memoirs of Tony Mendes.
The Affleck film is a special combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a real political thriller, the so-called “film-movie-opus”, the story of a successful venture, a scam - an example can be a number of films about Ocean’s friends.
The film is constantly changing moods - on the one hand, documented scenes from Tehran (the credits show the iconic historical photos of the events and how the same situations were demonstrated in the film - there is no big difference in this).
On the other hand, lighter Hollywood passages intersecting with irony and moderate exaggeration.
And then there are scenes from the headquarters of the CIA and other institutions - men in suits discuss the situation at the negotiating tables, on the stairs of institutions, on the phone ...
Ben Affleck had a great career.
From a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director, and his play ceased to be an object of ridicule.
“Operation Argo” is his third feature film, after the dark detective “Goodbye, baby, goodbye” (2007) and the thriller “City” (2010).
At the same time, this is the first Affleck film that is not filmed in the director’s hometown of Boston.
The feeling of the atmosphere of the place at the same time refers to the qualities that elevated earlier films of the director above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck shows it in Argo, where Tehran is “playing” Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place on the streets, when reconstructing real events - the opening scenes of the fall of the embassy impress with their clarity, which also conveys the emotions of confusion and unpredictability that arise when a story suddenly changes somewhere.
Affleck and his colleagues achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (fake headquarters in the Tehran bazaar).
There are too many processes in too many places.
The director had to deal with the fact that the story does not involve many exciting scenes of cinematic significance.
He works quite successfully with this few, sometimes thinking something up - there it all comes out not so elegant (the scene in which a phone call in America prevents the impending crisis at the airport of Tehran, and the pursuit of the runway look rather far-fetched).
The disadvantage of "Argo" is the distraction associated with the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman as Hollywood colleagues are really very charming, but their characters would deserve more space, and they are not the only ones in the film.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of drama, it is a film that can be watched with moderate interest, evaluating the production and retro style, recreating the thrillers of the seventies.
But it's hard to capture.
However, this is enough to remind us of one, still in a certain sense of living history, as well as to show how exaggerated are the ideas about omnipotent and omniscient special services.
Rules for inflating balloons, bananas and circus
The portal www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which annually conducts a survey on the most absurd bank fees, has now decided to announce a competition for "the most absurd regulation or project from the EU workshop."
“We were driven to this by the latest event in which the EU plans to adopt a 40 percent quota for women in the administration of large European companies,” said the organizer of the survey Patrick Nager.
Among the absurdities that have already been nominated is the recent decision of the European Court of Justice to combine the rate of insurance premiums for men and women.
Until now, women have had life insurance benefits because for insurance companies they are objectively less at risk.
“Further incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be put forward by the end of this year.
The voting itself will take place until the end of February 2013," Nager said.
Controversial EU regulations include, for example, the mandatory addition of biocomponents to fuel, which as a result is harmful to nature, as well as a ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers just because they contain relatively small amounts of dangerous substances, or a directive on the size of the cage for chickens, as a result of which eggs have risen significantly this year.
Also criticized was the de facto ban on the use of the term "butter oil" or the withdrawal from the sale of classic light bulbs.
Qualitative bananas should be 14 centimeters long.
The pan-European apparatus often makes a decision under the pressure of a trade or industrial lobby, whose positions in Brussels are usually defended by some state or group of states (thus the Czech Republic now even defends the demands of its banks under threat).
Lobby interests are as follows: for example, bananas of the highest quality in the European Union had to reach a length of 14 cm and did not dare to show "abnormal curvature".
At the same time, the European Commission justified itself by the fact that it only harmonizes the existing disparate national rules that complicated trade.
The EU, despite resistance from some states, has softened standards for fruits and vegetables, citing that existing directives will lead to waste products.
The candidate for winning in the survey may be last year’s EU regulation, according to which sold balloons must be provided with a warning that children under eight years of age can not inflate them without adult supervision.
The EU has turned to American studies, according to which balloons when playing are a potential cause of death of children by suffocation.
Such a restriction now applies to children under 14 years of age, who are prohibited from blowing in fair duvets.
Funny ideas are born at home.
The rule concerning European officials themselves is quite absurd: anyone who has any official position in the EU cannot, given the sensitivity of the topic for Greece, use the name Macedonia, but should instead say “FYROM” (the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
The portal Bankovna poplatky.com, in cooperation with the association of liberal economists "The principle of non-interference" (Laissez Faire), proposed for voting, in addition to a few of the above absurd rules, for example, the EU rule on the volume of food reserves in the territory of a member state.
The EU has set the maximum amount of food reserves that may be in the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of its accession to the European Union.
Subsequently, the Czech Republic exceeded, for example, the established volumes of canned mushrooms, for which it faced a large fine.
The organizers of the survey were also interested in the idea of paying some countries for the fact that they do not have the sea, and the idea of granting subsidies for the application for subsidies.
But these ideas originated in Prague, not in Brussels.
“We are at a disadvantage because we don’t have a sea.
We will ask the European Union for compensation,” said then-Minister of Agriculture Yaroslav Palas (ChSDP) in the fall of 2004.
As an argument, he pointed out that there was a high grain harvest in the country, and as a result of the so-called intervention purchases, the state had full stocks that had to be removed.
For the fact that the Czech Republic is far from ports, the EU, according to Palas, had to pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
As a result, the European Commission met the Czech Republic by organizing a tender for the purchase of grain from landlocked countries.
Subsidies for subsidies were offered to villages by the Ministry for Regional Development, led by Minister Pavel Nemets (US-DEU), in particular, such subsidies were to be used to draw up an application for subsidies from Brussels.
EU: Bizarre orders are an exception
Although regulations in member states are easily criticized, the EU’s efforts to regulate as well as improve the functioning and development of the European Union, according to many experts, deserve more recognition.
A serious problem, according to experts, is drawing EU subsidies for projects that do not even have a hint of something in common with the deepening of European integration, but which Member States achieved when discussing the budget.
The Czech Republic, as in other EU countries, should fight in Brussels for the right to a specific identification of its traditional products, and it does not always win this competition.
Although the Czechs after six years of fighting with the Germans and Austrians retained the name "Olomouc cheeses", but "Tuzemsky rum", the traditions of which in our country are rooted in the 19th century, our manufacturers had to be renamed "Tuzemak".
Only products from cane distillate, not sugar beets, can be called rum.
In the official list of registered products of the EU, along with the world-famous cheeses "feta" and "gorgondzola", marzipan from the German Lubeck or Parma ham, have already been, for example, Karlovy Vary crackers, Pogorzhelitsky and Treshebonsky carp and Zhatetsky hops.
Also, the EU trademark can be proud of Pardubic gingerbread and mustard straws.
