You will get the smell of rakfiska - one of the most famous Norwegian delicacies.
I am in a small town called Fagernes, three hours drive from Oslo.
Around the snow-covered scenic views. It is very beautiful, but in the air spreads ineradicable characteristic smell.
Rakfisk is a trout sprinkled with salt and fermented in water for up to a year, depending on what kind of soul you need to achieve.
As the twilight gets thicker and colder, crowds of Norwegians gather for a festival in Fagernes dedicated to this most, let’s say, exciting dish.
"It is eaten raw and washed down with a glass of aquavit, a local cumin vodka," explains Haward Halvarsen, a local firefighter by profession and part-time "racfiscal general" who runs the festival.
Everywhere around us, people eat fish sliced in small cubes and drink it with considerable portions of alcohol.
“Someone likes aquavit more than rakfisk,” says Howard.
This drink can break the smell.
I'm trying a few pieces.
If you manage to carry a piece under your nose, then everything is not so bad - it is not much different from the portion of sushi that you took with you on the bus for a long time.
Rakfisk is a Norwegian product from a completely different time, the time of poverty, when, even before the advent of refrigerators, fish was soaked in hermetically sealed barrels of salt water in the autumn.
Then in the deep winter, when the fish was already well and thoroughly fermented, it was extracted and, muted by alcohol perception, consumed for food.
The fact that thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and emigrate, mainly to the United States, is still remembered by the past generation.
Now the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, who are attracted by jobs, high wages and a developed social security system.
Residents of Sweden (a longtime rival, and not so long ago and a much more prosperous neighbor) come here to work en masse.
Rakfisk is perceived as an important symbol, an indispensable, albeit somewhat malevolent element of Norway’s past.
This is one of the most expensive local dishes.
On the other hand, everything is expensive here - a small glass of beer or a sandwich will cost you 9 pounds (14 US dollars).
Norway rarely appears in the world news, and most people in the country seem to be satisfied with this.
People here are still reluctant to mention the name of Anders Breivik, a racist and right-wing extremist who shot and killed 77 men, women and children last year.
Without mentioning his name, the terrorist attack is called "the July 22nd".
It is very difficult for Norwegians to believe that in their peace-loving country one of their fellow citizens was capable of such atrocities and murders.
At the heart of Norway’s current prosperity is the growth (since the early seventies) of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world.
“Oil is not the only reason for our prosperity, however,” says Anna, our waitress, who carries trays of aged raccoon, a woman with long blond hair and strikingly blue eyes, the epitome of Nordic well-being.
We are such a people - as you call it - reasonable.
Like most Norwegians, she speaks excellent English.
We don't like to show up, we're not bragging.
Norway is very careful with its oil - most of the revenues of the oil and gas industry are invested in a special fund created for the benefit of future generations.
In the years leading up to the global financial crisis, when everyone squandered money they didn’t have, Norway calculated the costs sparingly.
“As long as you can ski in the winter and hike in the summer, that’s enough for happiness,” says Anna.
"And there's rakfisk," she adds with a carefree laugh.
I'm standing in the snow in line for some food - I've had enough rakfiska.
Here's a hamburger with salmon meat - it's definitely exotic, delicious juicy meat.
But in the evening we are waiting for even more of the same fish with an unforgettable smell.
A special Rakfisk dinner is held at my hotel, during which visitors vote on the best or perhaps the most fragrant fish.
There is a direct TV air, in which the presenter is shown in a bow tie, surrounded by plates with a rakfisk.
It's like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"So, Thor-Jurgen, what's your estimate for the best fish out there in your mountains?"
"Yes, Howard, that's our assessment."
Everyone laughs and applauds.
Someone falls out of a chair, possibly overtaking the aquavit.
Or maybe just by smelling the fish.
Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto is facing a difficult start to his career.
As Mexico’s newly elected President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant invites us to take a look at the difficulties he will face and the mixed expectations of his country’s population.
Traffic in Mexico City is now in a particularly deplorable state.
This city is overloaded with transport and at the best time, and since Monday steel barriers have been erected, cutting several key highways to the capital and causing chaos on the roads.
However, this was not done to prevent people from getting to work from the suburbs, but to prevent protesters from getting to the parliament building.
On Sunday, Mexico’s new head of state, Enrique Pena Nieto, will put on a presidential tie and take the reins of the country.
He faces a difficult task.
Mexico has achieved good economic performance under the administration of Felipe Calderon, which is now resigning, but the country is mired in the war on drugs, which in six years has already claimed about 60,000 lives.
“My government is declaring to the people of Mexico its readiness to fight violence,” Mr. Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office of the White House earlier this week.
I am going to propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve this goal.
Prior to such statements, the political career of Mr. Pena Nieto developed alongside the President of the United States as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In his homeland, in the densely populated and vast state surrounding the capital of the country, opinions about the new leader were divided.
The Straight Man
In the idyllic town of Valle de Bravo, for example, it is remembered with warmth.
Residents credit him with the revival of tourism, the development of the resort sector and the creation of infrastructure.
The city can be reached by one of the new highways built by Mr. Pena Nieto, which are strikingly different from the roads with potholes and pits that were previously on the site.
Signs with his name hang on the modern building of the sports center and on the impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
“We have hopes for real and serious change with him,” says his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a state congressman from the Pena Nieto-led Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI).
We look forward to the real and decisive changes that are so urgently needed in our country, especially in the area of security and economic development.
After 81 years in power, the PRI party was supplanted in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that after his 12-year absence from the Los Pinos presidential palace, the party has high hopes for Enrique Pena Nieto.
In addition, he refutes the accusations of lack of content that the opposition has put forward to the new president.
He is very direct and very committed to the realization of his vision of the future of the country.
He is an excellent statesman, and, above all, a man who knows how to listen.
But in another part of the state, many people have a different idea of the former governor.
The municipality of Nesahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Nesa, is the most striking contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle de Bravo.
Hidden under the overpasses of highways, it is in many ways a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the municipality are also severe in nature of this metropolis.
Earlier this year, troops were deployed to quell drug-trafficking gangs in those areas, and violence against women is particularly acute.
Dozens of bodies of murdered women have been found in a wasteland near a large dump in the last two years alone.
More than 1,000 women were killed in Mexico State during the governorship of Mr. Pena Nieto, a figure far higher than that of the notoriously violent city of Ciudad Juarez, whose name has become a household name when it comes to killing innocent women.
According to Mr. Pena Nieto ' s opponents, he was at best not able to cope with the problem of women ' s murder during his term as governor.
In the worst case, his administration is accused of completely ignoring this problem.
A resident of a concrete house similar to most homes in this dilapidated area, Irineya Buendia struggles to hold back tears by showing me photos of her late daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that she was killed by her boyfriend.
“When I got to her house, it looked like her body had been washed before,” Ms. Buendia recalls.
There were signs that she had been beaten, and the body was already hamstrung.
Mariana’s mother recounts this story, and the portrait of her daughter looks at us from the wall, where he hangs next to the crucifix, which is inscribed with only one word: justice.
This, they said, was what the family was denied.
“State officials treated me like an old gossip, a disgruntled troublemaker.
They want people to just take everything they say and keep quiet.
But it’s wrong, it’s impossible, especially when there are so many violations and shortcomings around,” she says.
After putting on the presidential bandage on Saturday, President Pena Nieto will take on a difficult responsibility with her.
Over the past six years, tens of thousands of families in Mexico have been affected by violent crimes, and the new president has promised to make addressing this issue a priority during his presidency.
“I hope that he will be exactly the same president as he was the governor,” says Olvera, a congressman from Valle de Bravo from the PRI party.
However, this is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Ness are most afraid of.
Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, the prosecution claims.
Prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning’s claims about poor detention conditions.
The hearing focused on Manning's time in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense demands that the case be closed on the grounds that Manning's conditions of detention were cruel.
A U.S. Army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified materials in U.S. history, did not take advantage of many opportunities to file a complaint of ill-treatment, which, according to him, he had to endure while in military prison.
During a cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Meade, Maryland, military prosecutor Major Ashden Fein said that records of Manning's weekly visits by prison officials for nine months of his detention in Quantico, Virginia, contained no complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination, as part of the defence's motion to dismiss Manning's case on the grounds that the conditions of his detention were cruel and in themselves a sufficient punishment, was held the day after Manning stated that while in custody he had intended to commit suicide.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the Internet on the WikiLeaks website.
WikiLeaks did not confirm that Manning was the source of the information.
During Friday’s hearing, Attorney Fein, along with Manning, reviewed reports that were filled out after Manning’s visits by administration officials during his time in Quantico prison, where he was under strict detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, the prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Attorney Fein asked about the reports on Friday, Manning admitted that he regarded the treatment by the prison administration as "excellent" and the general conditions of detention as "very professionally organized."
The reports examined do not contain complaints of ill-treatment, despite Manning being directly asked about the conditions of his detention, Fein claims.
Manning replied that he had expressed verbal concern about these problems and that the administration officials who visited him had discussed these problems with him and stated that they would deal with them, but did not record this in writing.
“They were recording ‘problems are missing’ (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn’t mean I didn’t bring it up in conversation,” Manning says.
A military judge, Col. Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not complained about his mistreatment in January 2011 during a panel meeting considering suicidal intent, which he had expressed in writing months earlier.
Manning replied that during that meeting, he wanted to get the "injury prevention" regime lifted and the conditions of imprisonment relaxed.
The military officials explained that the limited detention regime - a level lower than the regime of supervision to prevent suicide - was introduced to protect the prisoner, as well as for the safety of others.
“I wanted to let the administration know that I’m okay with them canceling the injury prevention regime... so that my standard of living improves, from my point of view,” Manning explained.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that he had thoughts of suicide in Kuwait, and that he had lost consciousness one day due to the intense heat.
He explained that psychologically it is very difficult when you are not allowed to know how your fate is decided, and what is happening in the outside world.
“My world has shrunk to Camp Arifjean, to the size of my prison,” Manning said Thursday.
“I thought I was going to die in that cage.”
While in Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small cell — at least 21 hours, and often even more than 23 hours a day — all alone.
Manning says he was only allowed to leave a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, some clothes and glasses.
He says that he tried to move, as sleeping or even just lying in the daytime prohibited the rules.
According to Manning, during sleep in his eyes constantly beat light penetrating the outside of the camera.
If the guards did not see his face when he was turned over in bed at night, he said, he was woken up and forced to turn on his back.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal objection to Manning's mistreatment in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
In addition, on Friday, the judge asked Manning about a statement he made during his testimony on Thursday, that after one night he was forced to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners at a morning check-up.
Manning said he was unable to cover himself with a blanket during the inspection.
Responding to the judge’s questions on Friday, Manning said he understood from the guard’s order that he should throw a blanket that could be covered, but admitted that no one directly ordered him to throw it.
On Thursday, Manning said he was forced to sleep naked the previous night because of his attempt to show the officer that he posed no danger to himself.
Manning reported that he told the officer that he could use a rubber band of underpants or flip-flops to injure himself, but did not.
That night, according to Manning, his underwear, flip-flops and glasses were taken from the cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account what he had to go through during his imprisonment, and significantly reduce the term of imprisonment, if Manning is found guilty by a military court, which is due to begin consideration of his case early next year.
The defense said it planned to ask Manning to plead guilty to less serious crimes, and to challenge other charges as excessive.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to insist that the conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was detained in Quantico under the rules governing the detention of detainees with the most stringent regime.
Manning's charges include aiding and abetting the enemy, illegally facilitating the publication of data on the Internet, transmitting information related to national defense, and stealing state property or documents.
If convicted on all counts of the indictment, he could face life imprisonment.
My crisis of national self-determination is the story of an American of Mexican descent.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico for lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left because they remind the country’s residents of difficult times.
Ruben Navarette believes that Mexicans of American descent are torn between two cultures.
During a recent trip to Mexico City, I walked down the arrival corridor, approached the border control zone, and froze on the spot.
The signs indicated two lines: one for Mexicanos (Mexicans), the second for Extranjeros (foreigners).
I stood in front of them for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in central California and have been called a Mexican all my life.
It’s just a conventional name, just like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and my friends in New York consider themselves Italian.
Later, I settled on the complex design of an “American of Mexican origin.”
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather’s homeland, there was no need for conventional names or complex constructions.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than that of native speakers, and I can't get rid of the American accent.
So I got my American passport and got in line for Extranjeros.
I remembered this story a few days ago when the newly elected President of Mexico, Enrique Pena Nieto, visited the White House and met with President Obama.
The agenda included issues familiar to the presidents of these countries: immigration, drugs and trade.
President Pena Nieto was eager to talk about the recovery of the Mexican economy, thanks to which Mexicans will now be able to stay in Mexico, instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to sign a partnership agreement with the United States and Canada and create a kind of North American trade bloc like the European Union.
In addition, President Pena Nieto promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no specific proposals were made.
For Mexico, relations with the United States are a difficult and old-fashioned issue.
Most Americans never thought about the fact that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to give up half of their territory at gunpoint.
But Mexicans think for centuries, not minutes, and see reminders of those events in everything.
Therefore, it is only necessary for any US statesman to mention at least a word of criticism towards Mexico, complaints are immediately heard in the press and among the elite of Mexican society that Americans are encroaching on the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the descendants of Montezuma are filled with militancy.
Mexico’s relationship with more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States is the most difficult.
Do you want to talk about grievances?
There's enough.
In Mexico, there are winners and losers, people who find opportunities for themselves in this country, and those for whom there are no such opportunities.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio, there are so many people of Mexican descent for just one reason: at some point in their family history, someone — a father or grandfather — had no opportunity to realize themselves in Mexico and was forced to go north.
Most often they were Mexicans of a certain type - dark, poorly educated, from poor peasant families.
We are their descendants, and we remember that.
This is seen differently in Mexico.
Today, our life is the embodiment of the American dream, we studied in good schools and got good jobs, but we will not forget that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confusing and unclear, but we know which country to consider as our own.
United States of America.
In addition, we know that most representatives of the Mexican elite and the ruling class do not like us.
We answer them the same way.
They see us as a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us like second-class people, like fake Mexicans.
We don’t speak Spanish well enough, and our ties with Mexico are not strong enough.
Our very existence for them is explained by failures.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
We would not now be behind the silk curtain, finding a satisfying life in the United States, but losing spiritual ties.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and legally moved to the U.S. as a child, and it reminds me that there are certain tensions between real Mexicans and Mexican Americans - Mexicans understand their national identity more clearly, and Mexican Americans are offended.
She is a U.S. citizen and believes she belongs to both countries.
At the same time, many of my Mexican-American acquaintances do not feel that they belong to any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
When you get the best of both worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
We are Americans in Mexico.
In the United States, we are called Mexicans.
Now, as I found out during my trip, as if our relations are not already sufficiently complicated, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to restore relations with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as Mexican ambassadors and represent Mexican interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends what a wonderful country it is and how great it is to visit, and we could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, sure.
It's not gonna work.
Too many grievances in the past.
And given the gap between rich and poor, rampant corruption and drug trafficking, many of us do not consider this country so beautiful.
I'm sorry, but deal with it yourself, amigos.
And it's fair.
If some Mexicans still cannot forgive the United States for what it did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still resentful of the way their relatives were treated in Mexico more recently.
Yeah.
I think we have more in common than I thought.
Old battles in the new Middle East
A cease-fire between Israel and Hamas could be a fragile foundation for further peace
Can there be lasting peace between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion of the futility of such hopes.
There is a familiar, pointless debate about who started it; many buildings have been turned into ruins; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; and for the first time since the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip have fallen in the vicinity of Israel's capital, Tel Aviv, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
However, despite the fact that Israelis and Palestinians are hopelessly mired in their age-old conflict, changes have come to the Middle East.
This can be treated in different ways, but the events of the “Arab Spring” have swirled in a rebellious storm of many well-established realities, and the Palestinians and the Israelis have not managed to stay away from the vortex that shook the region.
Perhaps, as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons to hope for a way out of this deadly impasse.
War Without Winners
At first glance, the current situation does not give grounds for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on November 21, is implemented, the clashes that occurred this week only strengthened the positions of security forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Islamist movement Hamas, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, will say that they forced Israel to retreat, despite the losses they suffered.
Despite the fact that some of the group’s leaders have been destroyed, and 1.7 million residents are blocked in one of the most densely populated and problematic corners of our planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is growing its popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory currently controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time is working for them.
With the growing influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world, Hamas has new influential and wealthy friends.
A resurgent regional leader, Turkey, which was once Israel’s closest ally among Muslim nations, has come out in support of Hamas; it was followed by Qatar, one of the richest and fastest-growing states in the Persian Gulf.
Prominent Hamas supporters claim to have established an Islamist crescent around Israel, from Lebanon in the north, ruled by Hezbollah, to Syria, where increasingly pro-Islamist rebels are about to overthrow Bashar al-Assad, and on to Jordan, where the king’s power is threatened by Hamas allies.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region occurred on the southern borders of Israel, in the most populous and important Arab country, Egypt, where under President Mohamed Morsi, the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood was strengthened.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was deposed in 2011, was a secular dictator who did not pay much attention to supporting Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, by contrast, is an organization much like Hamas, and its leaders are more prone to populism.
In future diplomatic settings, Hamas may become a significant player whose voice will not be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the “hard” line in Israel will come to opposite conclusions.
In a military sense, Hamas was defeated.
Israel’s Iron Dome anti-missile system has justified the cost of building it and has successfully destroyed many of the rockets launched by Hamas.
Israeli citizens can sleep peacefully, at least for a while.
In terms of diplomacy, the U.S. has remained true to its unwavering position; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for the latest round of violence.
Another important factor is the economic prosperity of Israel, especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, who largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that some 30 Israelis have been killed by rockets fired from Gaza since 2004, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of suicide bombers, in part due to the wall that enters the West Bank - a large part of the unrecognized Palestinian state - and protects Jewish settlements, which continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions in terms of international law.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party - in preparation for the elections scheduled for January 22 - united with even more aggressive conservatives under the leadership of Avigdor Lieberman, is very convenient.
What's the point of pandering to the Palestinians and giving them their own state?
If all power is given to them in the West Bank, will they not launch rockets toward Israel, as their counterparts in the Gaza Strip do?
It is better to keep them behind the wall and harshly suppress any attempts to raise their heads.
It is possible that the hardliners will win; however, their calculations can be refuted by the Arab spring.
While Islamists who come to power in Egypt and other countries have not the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than all of its Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with a regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of Egypt’s president, Morsi, who worked with Barack Obama on a ceasefire, is a good sign and could mark the beginning of a change.
Israel, no less, must take into account the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic change approaches in Arab countries, denying Palestinians the right to self-determination is a time bomb that will sooner or later explode in Israeli-occupied territories, much like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already undermining the foundations of the democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic aspect - the growth of the Arab population - only exacerbates these problems.
For the bloody operations that are carried out every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the movement of Hamas, it is necessary to pay the growing discontent of the international community.
Both sides need an external impulse.
There remains the only solution that sensible representatives on both sides, as well as much of the rest of the world and our newspaper, are relentlessly calling for: the formation of two states and Israel’s ceding territories in exchange for security.
There is hope, not too impressive in the short term, that a ceasefire will allow other countries to more effectively influence the parties to the conflict.
Egypt, which is long overdue for a decision to cut off arms supplies to the Gaza Strip, and Turkey and Qatar are more than ever in a position to persuade Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish state, adopted since 1967, given the exchange of territories and the joint use of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile the Hamas and Fatah movements.
This would do more to create a Palestinian state than the upcoming UN vote, which could result in the recognition of the virtual statehood of Palestine.
President Obama has a role to play in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never presented his own peace plan.
After returning to the White House, he still shows reluctance to join the solution to this problem.
This is a disastrously short-sighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is possible only in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, the Uniform Cigarette Packaging Act came into force.
Warnings about the dangers of smoking and images of diseased body parts are contrasted on dull green boxes, the same for all brands of cigarettes.
The first in the world practice of the Australian law on the same type of packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products came into force, replacing the logos and colors of different brands with the same box of dull-olive color with terrible pictures of diseased parts of the body and images of children whose health is undermined by the smoking of their parents.
In addition to various pictures and inscriptions warning about the dangers of smoking, the only difference between the packs, introduced mandatory from this Saturday - the names of brands that are printed in the same small print.
These are the most severe conditions in the world for the design of packages of tobacco products.
The Australian federal government says the goal is to keep young people out of smoking by stripping it of its status as a bad habit.
This decision was based on the results of studies that showed that people who did not start smoking before the age of 26 in 99 cases out of 100 never become smokers.
“It is obvious that even at a very young age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies try to convey with the help of packaging,” explains the Minister of Health Tanya Plibersek, referring to studies that showed, for example, that the crown in the logo is associated with the idea of a princess in children.
Australia is one of the countries with the lowest share of smokers in the world, so these changes will not particularly affect the profits of transnational corporations, but other countries are already considering taking such measures.
Representatives of the tobacco industry strongly opposed the adoption of this law.
Tobacco companies claim that this will only increase the share of the black market in which cheap and affordable cigarettes will be sold.
“This law will have serious consequences different from those conceived by its initiators,” said Scott McIntyre, a spokesman for British American Tobacco in Australia.
Manufacturers of counterfeit products from China and Indonesia will supply much more such goods for sale on the streets of Australia.
For some, on the contrary, new laws contribute to the growth of business.
Sandra Ha of the small family-owned company Zico Import Pty Ltd claims that demand for cigarette cases and silicone cases that hide unpleasant pictures on the packaging has grown rapidly (almost from scratch) since two months ago, companies such as British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost the case in the high court of Australia, where they tried to appeal the law.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold about six thousand products to wholesalers and expects a new batch.
This is good business for us.
A potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures is, according to experts, the popularity of social networks among precisely the part of the population to which these measures are aimed.
After the adoption of a number of laws in Australia that made illegal television advertising of cigarettes and their support of sporting events, as well as prohibiting sellers to display cigarettes in a prominent place, tobacco advertising moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned local companies and websites from advertising online, but it cannot restrict foreign sites.
“If you’re selling tobacco products and you only have this little loophole left, the idea of promoting your product online will seem extremely tempting,” explains Becky Freeman, who researches public health issues at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes an increase in the number of reviews of trademarks written on behalf of supposedly ordinary users on social networks such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question arises - is this really the work of an ordinary citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he spared no effort and time and made a video, or is there an advertising company behind it?
The Australian branch of British American Tobacco says that the industry is now more busy adapting to the new rules than advertising.
Representatives of the tobacco industry have even taken measures such as sponsoring Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: these states make claims within the World Trade Organization, claiming that trade has been unfairly restricted, despite the fact that trade relations between all these countries with Australia are very small.
The WTO decision is expected by mid-2013.
According to Tanya Plibersek, the government discussed with other countries the possibility of their adoption of similar laws on packaging.
In 2001, Canada was the first to introduce mandatory posting of photos warning of the dangers of smoking.
Now this rule is adopted in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
The possibility of tightening the laws is being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia defiantly disobey the innovations.
These pictures don't bother me.
I'm just not paying attention.
“Just take out a cigarette and put a pack in your pocket,” explains Victor El Haig, who buys cigarettes with a picture of a tumor of the oral cavity on the pack.
Honestly, the only thing that can make me leave is my little daughter.
James Yew, head of the tobacco store King of the Pack in central Sydney, says the same packaging has made it harder to put goods on shelves.
“I used to have an hour to unload a new party, and now it’s four hours,” he complains.
“The government had to take and completely ban cigarettes, we would then say: what to do, okay, it’s over, close the store,” he says, throwing his hands up.
To be bored in the world of electronic networks and permanent connections is not so bad.
On this Thanksgiving, I suddenly had to spend five hours at the airport because our plane had mechanical problems and was replaced by another plane, which we were waiting for.
So I had plenty of time to think about the nature of boredom.
I'm not gonna lie to you.
Half a day at the airport waiting for a flight is really boring, and neither books, nor magazines, nor iPhones, nor even duty-free shops will help much here.
However, recently, more and more scientists and specialists in children's development speak in favor of boredom.
They say that in certain situations for us and for our children to miss is not so bad.
This forces the brain to be distracted on interesting related topics, which may contribute to creativity.
And since in the modern world we are all constantly in front of some kind of screen, the benefits of boredom pass us by.
Maybe we should try to be bored?
Yeah.
And at the same time, no.
We'll get back to that.
I used to think, like many people, that boredom was an invention of relatively recent times, when people had more free time.
Peter Tui, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada, is the author of Boredom: A Lively History (Yale University Press, 2011).
“In fact, boredom can boast of a very ancient history,” he says.
On the walls in Pompeii found Latin inscriptions about boredom, dating back to the first century.
This leaves open the question of how we understand boredom.
The problem, says John D. Eastwood, an associate professor at York University in Ontario, Canada, is that the understanding and vision of boredom has often changed.
After reviewing research on this topic and asking a question to a target group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the following definition: boredom is when people "want, but can not do what would bring them satisfaction."
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a bored person doesn’t do something they’d like to do.
With apathy, you do not want to do anything.
The main thing in the experience of boredom, he says, is “disruption of attention and the associated deterioration of mood and the feeling that time is slow.”
The description of boredom may seem very similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood argues that despite the possible connection between these conditions, bored people see the causes of problems in the world and circumstances, and people experiencing depression see problems in themselves.
Sometimes we feel bored when it’s really hard for us to focus on something.
In their study, Unemployed Mind: Defining Boring in terms of Attention, published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues refer to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a recording of a voice reading a journal.
Some participants also heard loud noises from an off-the-record television program included in the next room, others heard the same noises at low volume so that they could barely be disassembled, and a third group listened only to a voice recording without an extraneous sound track.
Those participants who heard low-volume TV noted that they were bored, more often than others - they had difficulty concentrating, but they did not know the reason for this and attributed it to boredom.
When we try to focus on a difficult or exciting task, attention interruption can be boring, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neurology at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the authors of this study.
On the other hand, when we do something uninteresting, “for example, peering into the flow of products on the assembly line in search of marriage, distracting music can help avoid boredom.”
It is believed, he continues, that when people begin to sway on a chair or draw doodles on a piece of paper, they do it out of boredom, but now we know that in fact such actions simply help not to relax physically.
“The study showed that children who are not forbidden to fiddle and spin learn better and remember more information than children who are required to sit still,” says Professor Fenske.
At some point, we are all bored: when the flight is delayed (as in my case), listening to monotonous speech, watching an uninteresting film.
However, different people show varying degrees of boredom.
In the 1980s, to measure such individual characteristics, researchers developed a special “boring bias scale.”
To determine the score on this scale, questions and statements are used, for example, "Much of what I have to do is monotonous and monotonous" or "I am too much interested, so there is not enough time for anything."
Using such questionnaires, the researchers determined that boys are bored more often than girls, says Steven Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially in the presence of a variety of external stimuli.
However, in general, teenagers are often bored.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personal and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents 7-8 times a day.
He got the following results: 32% of teens said they were bored at school and while doing homework, and 23% said they were bored outside of school.
Only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson notes that he has no data on what would be such data about boredom now, 21 years later.
However, he knows that “adolescence has a peak tendency to boredom”, mainly because children and adolescents are not allowed to fully decide what to do.
Back to my original question: Is boredom useful?
Sometimes it is not, because in extreme cases, as studies show, it can push people to absurd and dangerous physical actions, risky gambling or abuse of certain substances in an attempt to get rid of boredom.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have thought about the connection between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovich, who has devoted more than two decades to the study of this problem.
“So our brain tells us to do something else; that’s boredom,” says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
However, this same brain does not always know what is best to do.
If you’re bored and you direct that energy to playing guitar or cooking experiences, you’ll make yourself better.
However, if you start watching TV, you will only get better for a while, and soon it will pass.
Therefore, if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he will stop being bored, but he will not learn how to deal with boredom on his own or in any other way manage his time and employment,” says Professor Fenske.
“And such self-regulatory skills are used in a variety of situations,” he says.
Your child learns not only to occupy himself with something, he also learns self-control in general.
I don't think boredom needs to be extolled in any way.
However, to consider it something bad is also not worth it.
Rather, you should learn to feel comfortable even outside the continuous flow of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
“We see this as something that we need to be bored more often, even though boredom is an extremely unpleasant, unquenchable desire to do something meaningful,” he says.
In fact, people tend to somehow disconnect from constant worries and just relax.
“In today’s world, we’re used to the constant over-stimulation of the senses,” he says, “and when there’s silence, we get lost and don’t know what to do.”
It is unclear how the new law on the legalization of marijuana in Colorado will be applied.
Anthony Orosco, a 19-year-old football player and community college student in southeastern Colorado, is charged with a criminal offense that would soon be perfectly legal throughout the state: keeping a small portion of marijuana and the tube in which he smoked it.
Mr Orozco says he and his friends were in Lamar one day in September driving a car down a prairie near the Kansas border when they were stopped by police.
After a policeman found marijuana in the car, Mr. Orozco went to court for possession of drugs and possession of a device for drug use - minor offenses, for each of which a fine of $ 100 is due - and a date for the trial was set.
“We are treated like criminals,” Mr. Orozco says.
But is he a criminal?
As a result of the uncertainty that has been going on for weeks since the state of Colorado voted to legalize the use of marijuana in small quantities for entertainment, the resolution of hundreds of small court cases depends not so much on the law as on the location of the case.
Accusations of minor marijuana-related offenses are already being dropped in hundreds of cases here and in Washington State, which has taken a similar action.
Police stations have already stopped charging people aged 21 and older for possession of small doses, which will be considered legal as soon as the law comes into force in a couple of weeks.
However, in the more conservative districts of Colorado, prosecutors have decided to consider existing marijuana cases and continue to prosecute possession of the drug.
At the same time, in some cities from the suburbs of Denver to the mountainous areas of the West, they are voting to prevent the emergence of new, state-licensed marijuana stores in their places.
“It’s all going so fast that I don’t even know what to expect next,” said Daniel J. Oates, chief of police in Aurora, east of Denver.
Representatives of regulatory authorities in the state of Washington are also puzzled scratching their heads.
They will have to form rules to determine the procedure for licensing the cultivation, processing, distribution and sale of marijuana, and all this must be done before December 1, 2013.
They say Colorado, for better or for worse, is ahead of most other states in settling marijuana use issues, first for medical purposes and now for entertainment.
“There’s a more orderly market in Colorado, so they’ll set a good example,” said Brian E. Smith, a spokesman for the Washington State Alcohol Board.
But now no one can do more, Mr. Smith admits, than to put forward some suggestions and hope that it will work.
“We don’t have a real precedent that we can target,” he says.
The Washington state bill, called I-502, will come into force on December 6 and put the state into a state of uncertainty for a year when the state licensing system is not yet in place, and the right to own marijuana is already legal.
But there are still difficult technical aspects that need to be resolved during this period, for example, how to find a balance between the state's order for "adequate access" to licensed marijuana with a ban on trading it at a distance of 1000 feet from schools, parks, playgrounds and kindergartens.
“It will be particularly difficult to locate licensed marijuana businesses within cities, particularly in Seattle and its suburbs,” said Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the newly established Marijuana Legalization Center research group.
On November 21, Auths, a police chief from Aurora, sent an email to his subordinates saying that the city’s prosecutor’s office would no longer hold people under the age of 21 accountable for owning a small amount of marijuana, and that the police would stop incriminating people about these violations “starting from now on.”
Oates, the police chief, said police would monitor the city’s compliance with regulations governing medical marijuana growers and would prosecute drug traffickers and distributors.
Weld County Attorney in northern Colorado, Ken Buck, presents a more rigorous approach to the issue.
Following the vote on the bill, he stated that the prosecutor's office would continue to prosecute possession of marijuana, mainly to encourage its users to undergo treatment.
At the moment, 119 people have been charged with possession of two or fewer ounces of marijuana, although many of them are also accused of other violations.
“It is our agency’s duty to prosecute acts deemed criminal at the time they are committed,” Mr. Buck said in a statement.
The reaction was mixed even in places such as rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the proposal to legalize marijuana.
Grand Junction Police, the largest city in the county, no longer prosecute adults for possession of a small amount of the drug.
District Attorney Pete Houtzinger supported this decision, but also decided not to drop charges in already open cases related to marijuana possession.
“I believe that enforcing the law until it changes is our direct responsibility,” he says.
Although 55% of Colorado voters supported the decision, including marijuana for entertainment in the state and legal system will not be easy.
And the contradictory reaction of residents in different places of the state revealed the ambiguity of the attitude of local authorities to the experiment of the state with marijuana.
“There is a cultural barrier to district attorneys in this matter,” explains Sean McAllister, a Denver attorney representing marijuana possession convicts and a local representative for the National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws.
“They’ve been chasing people for so long for this that they can’t really accept that it’s no longer a crime,” he says.
Colorado and Washington — the first states to treat a small amount of marijuana in the same way as alcohol — are destined to become an experimental field nationwide to test the very idea of legalizing drugs.
Proponents of legalization and state officials plan to expand the territory of legalized trade, but at the same time they are wary of instructions from the federal authorities, which still plan to consider the sale and cultivation of marijuana as federal crimes.
Proponents of marijuana legalization hope that the Justice Department will concede on this issue.
Despite several high-profile arrests of drug dealers and patients who used marijuana for medical reasons, the federal government in most cases approved the sale of marijuana for medical purposes in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
Bureau of Narcotics agents are unlikely to break into homes to confiscate a small bag of marijuana, but they are unlikely to turn a blind eye to state-regulated recreational marijuana stores that are allowed under the new law, said Kevin A. Sabet, a former counter-narcotics adviser in the Obama administration.
Some cities in Colorado did not wait for the actions of the federal authorities.
Even before the presidential election, some local administrations approved a moratorium on the opening of new marijuana stores, which could not have opened sooner than a year later.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the western part of the state, put forward a six-month ban on the marijuana trade, which is likely to be approved next week.
“We don’t want to be in a position where we give someone a license, and then it will cause serious problems at the federal level,” says Bob Nicholson, a city council member.
The city voted against the amendment.
And now we have a contradiction between the results of the local vote and what the state voted for.
There are still many unresolved issues.
Petronella Wyatt: I survived Oxford for being a conservative.
The persecution of university students for their views did not begin today.
For as long as I can remember, I've always wanted to go to Oxford University.
My father and older brother studied at Oxford and described it as the best educational institution in the world, a modern analogue of the ancient symposium, laying the two foundations of civilization - freethinking and tolerance.
And yet, after two weeks of studying history at Oxford University’s Worcester College in the late eighties, I packed my bags and left, which resulted in the first real scandal in my life.
My father couldn't stand it and wept.
Friends were confused.
The Evening Standard claimed that I dropped out of college because I didn’t like my classmates having sex in the next room.
Writer E. Norman Wilson joked that I left because I had to drink from the crushed cups.
It wasn't really that much fun.
I ran away.
Yeah, she ran away because I was systematically bullied and bullied.
Not because of my rather unusual name or because I was in a private school.
I was bullied for only one reason, and in this illustrious cradle of enlightenment it looked like real barbarism and blind bigotry: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a well-known adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I was a conservative myself.
You might ask, why think about it now?
According to the latest data, a new generation of students who adhere to center-right views is subjected to the same harassment.
This institutionalized and ever-growing hatred of Conservative students in Oxford is so strong that last week a group of such students demanded the same protection of their rights as that granted to disabled, sexual and ethnic minorities.
Conservatives at Cambridge's Corpus Christi College student club say they are "often actively isolated, personally attacked and made to feel unwanted by guests" because of their political views.
They want to introduce an additional representative to the college's equal rights committee to ensure freedom of expression.
Their situation was only aggravated by the recently released BBC 2 documentary about politics in the student environment “Wonderland: young, smart and right”, in which conservatives were presented with eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
The film featured Joe Cook, former president of the Oxford University Conservative Association, who drives in a Rolls Royce, wears a silver suit and a cane with a silver braid.
In other universities, conservative students complain that they are made "scapegoats due to higher tuition fees."
Luke Black, 20, vice president of the University of Nottingham's Conservative Association, said in an interview with a Sunday newspaper that "in the university environment, there is an increasing bias towards left-wing views.
People who don’t even know us think of us as the brazen and rabid children of rich parents.”
Samuel Roberts, 21, a student in the history department of Corpus Christi College, where a petition for increased protection was filed, calls such an atmosphere "uncomfortable", and Stephanie Cheryl, 19, the new president of the Oxford University Conservative Association, says that the attitude of members of the student club to the carriers of right-wing views has deteriorated significantly.
“This poses a threat to both the atmosphere of intellectual debate and the normal lives of club members,” she said.
For the first few weeks at Oxford, I was not just in the minority, I was alone.
I went there in September 1986, a timid and shy eighteen-year-old girl.
Oxford was fevered by hatred of the Conservative Party.
A year earlier, the university voted to strip former student Margaret Thatcher of her honorary degree due to budget cuts for higher education.
In such an atmosphere, even the Stalinists would be uncomfortable.
In the early days of freshman week, when the students get to know each other and the teachers, I felt for the first time what was ahead of me.
I did not know that teachers not only looked past their fingers at the harassment of conservative students, but also took part in it with pleasure.
Political issues - the miners' strike, privatization and the government's refusal to impose sanctions against the apartheid government in South Africa - penetrated the walls of the auditoriums sheathed with wooden panels.
At my first seminar I needed to translate the eighteenth-century French text into English, and I was not prepared for what followed.
"Miss Wyatt," said the late Harry Pitt, "please translate the first paragraph."
It was hard for me, I was stuck.
Harry Pitt was a very bile person with a face that looked like a cake.
“The Thatcherites don’t learn French, or do they just lack brains?” he asked.
Other students giggled.
There were tears in my eyes.
“I advise you to take a few initial French lessons in your spare time, if you are not very busy, rotating in society,” said Pitt.
I went back to my room completely unhappy.
That night in college, I was sitting at lunch alone; then someone patted me on the shoulder.
It was James, a second-year English student who introduced himself as a member of the University's Conservative Association.
"I know who you are," he said friendly.
- Unfortunately, the situation is as follows:
Anyone suspected of being conservative will be bullied.
It's not easy for me, and in your case, they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's gonna be harder for you.
Most freshman Conservatives pretend to be Labour.
Later, in the local pub, I tried to be hypocritical.
I insisted that I didn't agree with everything Margaret Thatcher said.
The trick didn't work.
A freshman at the Faculty of Philosophy, Politics and Economics, who studied at Eton himself, said: “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You're contagious."
Other students picked up on his words.
I was spoiled, dirty.
"How do conservatives have sex?" one asked.
- They're stabbing each other, aren't they?"
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before criminal prosecution was abolished in the sixties.
Will I ever be able to live a normal life in Oxford?
Or do I have to meet with like-minded people only under cover of night?
Will I be forced to become a Labourer and hide my true beliefs?
The next three years have come to seem like hell, full of persecution and loneliness.
The only teacher in my college who did not hide his conservative views was Norman Stone, a professor of modern history.
He was hated not only for belonging to conservatives, but also for being Thatcher's foreign policy adviser and one of her speechwriters.
He hardly showed up at college.
He despised him for his provincialism, pettiness, and commitment to a Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997, he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
“You won’t be happy here,” he told me.
I began to travel to Oxford from my parents’ home in London, trying to find refuge among relatives and unbiased metropolitan friends.
I told my dad I hated Oxford and explained why.
He didn't believe me.
During his studies in the forties, any political views were adopted there.
"But it's the best university in the world," he said complaining.
- They can't do that, but not in the city of dormant spires...
Even my Communist friends have always behaved flawlessly.”
His wet eyes are clouded.
“Don’t make hasty decisions.
I'm sure it's just a joke.
You'll break my heart if you drop out of college."
I was exhausted by the constant trips to London and my emotional protection weakened.
My friend, also a conservative, couldn’t stand the pressure and gave up on his beliefs.
The next week during a seminar, when another history teacher quite seriously called me an “enemy of the people”, I decided to do the same.
In my heart, burning with shame, I confessed that "my parents brainwashed me," and called them "old fools."
The respite was short-lived.
The last nail in the coffin of my Oxford career was destined for my father.
At the time, he wrote two columns each week for publications owned by Rupert Murdoch.
My door was locked.
I didn't go out, and five minutes later my pursuers gave up.
When they left, I packed my suitcase and got on the first train to London.
I never came back.
You can call me cry and rag.
But at eighteen, no one should be the object of such anger and intimidation in an educational institution.
The saddest thing is that it was Oxford, who not only released fourteen Tory prime ministers, but to this day hides behind the undeserved reputation of a university that values equality and freethinking.
"Valentino prefers elegance to fame"
About the exhibition "Valentino: Master Sewing", which opened this week in London, ABC talks with Nati Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemitz and other famous clients of the Italian designer
Somerset House, the former residence of Queen Elizabeth I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy to host an exhibition about Valentino Garavani.
The designer acknowledged this during the opening of "Valentino: Master Sewing", a triumphant retrospective exhibition that brings together more than 130 high-fashion dresses created by his "house" over the past 50 years.
“I love this palace,” he says with his unique Italian accent.
This exhibition is the final part of the story, the only character of which is "Il Signore" Garavani, but it could not be written without his famous clients.
Valentino has always felt fascinated by the rare and distant world of the nobility.
The first hall of this exhibition, open until March 3, abounds with personal letters and photographs signed by the most noble aristocrats, from Princess Salima Aga Khan to Lord Snowdon, including Marie-Chantal, Princess of Greece, and Margaret, Princess of Great Britain.
Valentino shows these personal memories as trophies of his social rise: from a modest tailor from the city of Voguera in northern Italy to the idol of the international “elite”.
Being in love with the royal court is not a bad thing.
“At least they don’t extinguish the cigarette butts on your gorgeous carpet, like some beautiful pop stars do,” says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemitza.
In the 60s and 70s we both lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is an unparalleled host and welcomes guests with generosity and elegance.
"We all really liked to come to his chalet in Gstaad," explains the ex-wife of Hainy Thyssen, a close friend of forgotten beauties like Marella Agnelli or Eugenia Niarchos.
Valentino always preferred elegance to fame.
Despite this, he is a star.
Valeria Mazza representing Valentino
Argentine model Valeria Mazza remembers a charismatic fashion designer.
One day we went to dinner at his house, it was after the fashion show in the Plaza de Espana in Rome, many years ago.
Among the twenty invited were Sharon Stone and John Kennedy Jr.
Valentino's style manifested itself in everything - in every detail of his apartment, in its decoration, in food, in music.
“Valentino made each of the guests feel important and loved,” recalls the “top model”, whose work with the fashion designer began in 1995 during the Fashion Week in Paris.
“He never goes out of fashion because his sketches are real works of art,” she concludes.
A parade of pedigrees
Garavani’s life is not a story of obsessions, but of love with full reciprocity.
He loves people with good upbringing and high titles, and they love him.
One of Somerset House's galleries has been turned into a glamorous sixty-meter-long leather runway that offers a change of roles: the visitor takes the place of models and has to defile on the runway, contemplating "viewers" of dreams that sparkle with masterpieces from Valentino, such as the dress that Jacqueline Kennedy chose for her wedding to Aristotle Onassis, a suit that was used by Monica Vitti.
In this public of models shine names such as Sibilla Luxembourg, Gloria von Turn und Taxis, Mette-Marit from Norway, Rosario from Bulgaria or Sofia Habsburg.
Nati Abaskal and fashion designer, in 2006
Many of these clients say that the first Valentino - as a first love, "it is impossible to forget."
I remember him perfectly.
These were pants, a shirt, a “jewel” and a jacket from the autumn-winter 1971-1972 collection.
“It was a gift he gave me,” says Nati Abascal, one of the designer’s muses.
“I prefer him to others for his femininity, for his great love for women, because he emphasizes our beauty,” adds the former Duchess de Feria.
I really like the colors he uses: they have a lot of light in them and they "fit" to his face.
The proportions are perfect.
Princess and trendsetter Patricia della Jovampaola d’Arenberg also can’t forget the first time she dressed in Valentino.
When I was a teenager and lived in Italy, I dreamed that I would have an age and a reason to wear one of his evening toilets.
That time finally came in the late 1990s.
I bought my first dress from Valentino to wear to the party at my cousin's castle, Prince Edward de Linh.
It was a red dress, with a skirt with frills, a "corsage" in the fold and a cutout without straps.
"It was a dream come true," says Rodrigo d'Arenberg's widow.
“Valentino is indifferent to fashion, his passion is timeless,” explains this Italian aristocrat who lives between Paris, New York and Buenos Aires.
Princess d'Arenberg keeps her holiday dresses from the fashion designer with "maximum caution... because the dress is not just a dress, it is also a collection of memories accompanying it."
The King of Fashion
The grand finale of the exhibition at Somerset House is Marie-Chantal Miller's wedding dress for her wedding to Pavlos from Greece in 1995.
It took four months of work and 25 "girls" (as the designer calls his seamstress) to make this outfit from ivory silk with pearl inlay, twelve kinds of various laces and a train of four and a half meters.
According to journalist Susie Menkes, the greatest authority of the specialized press, the dress represents a milestone of high fashion of the late XX century, "the return of clients from the upper world."
Fooled by the elite’s “lifestyle” for many years, Valentino himself is now its best representative.
Cavalier of the Grand Cross (a mark of distinction of the highest rank in Italy), Cavalier of Labor, Commander of the Order of Arts and Letters, awarded the Order of the Legion of Honor, Garavani collected as many honors as any of the spouses of his clients.
“My attention has always been drawn to his refinement, his calmness, his neat and flawless appearance,” says Arenberg.
The last time I saw him was at a gala dinner at the Musée d'Orsay a month ago.
He sat at the table with Countess Jacqueline de Ribe, my great friend.
"He was perfect, time doesn't exist for him."
If that's what the princess says...
The hardest profession in the world: miners from Kawah Ijen
For four euros, Indonesian miners risk their lives and health by dragging 70 kilograms of sulfur to the top of the volcano along steep rocky trails
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
Among them is Anto Vijaya, one of 400 miners who make their living by mining sulfur in the Kawah Ijen volcano, located in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day, Anto descends to the bottom of the crater, where sulfurous gas rising from the depths of the Earth freezes in contact with the air.
He split huge pieces of sulfur, the total weight of which can reach 70 kg, he puts them in two bamboo baskets, piles the baskets on his shoulders and carries them up a steep rocky road.
To the top of the volcano, which is 2.386 meters high, it takes only 250 meters, but it takes emaciated loaders more than 40 minutes to climb a turtle step, difficult to keep balance and carefully groping the road so as not to stumble and not fall off the cliff.
They know that one wrong step can cost them their lives, as happened to a tourist from France, who fell several years ago from the cliffs of Kawach-Ijen.
Kavah-Ijen miners earn 5 euro cents for every kilogram of sulphur mined
Once at the top, they make their way between tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, carrying heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scales that the mining company placed just above, at an altitude of 1,850 meters.
We are talking about PT Kandy Ngrimbi, an enterprise that has been operating this volcano since 1960 and, better not to say, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for each kilogram of sulfur.
Then it sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to petrochemical industries, because this mineral is common in everyday life and is used for making matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
"Since the norm is carrying 70 kilograms, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each walk," Anto, who usually performs three daily carryings, explains to us.
He spends three hours on each of them and feels broken at the end, however they allow him to accumulate 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) by the end of the day.
Although it seems a miniscule for such an inhuman effort, it is three times what he would earn in the field.
“The daily wage for miners is very high by local standards, where 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day are paid for coffee collection and the average monthly earnings are equal to two million rupees (167 euros),” explains the loader, who used to work as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the plot was not so heavy, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a good reason, which in Indonesia is as crushing as sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali, where there are some Hindus, and brought her to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, he breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly, and his eyes get teary because of toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto spent three years risking himself in Kavakh-Ijen, whose sulfur had already begun to affect him despite the presence of a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, he breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly, and his eyes get teary because of the toxic gases that the volcano emits.
That’s the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
“I’ll work two more years because I want to open a store or learn Spanish or French,” he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished by life, this pleasant and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or hotel porter, but instead he does the job of a mule.
Sharing a dirty wooden hut with other porters, he gets up every day at two in the morning, because sulfur does not cease to flow at night when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and glitters in the dark.
Challenging the shadows, Anto descends into the crater, lighting his way with a small lantern connected to his helmet, which he himself bought with his own money.
About 400 porters carry baskets of sulfur on their shoulders from the bottom of the volcano
Despite the high profits, the mining company has not mechanized the production of sulfur to save costs and does not provide any equipment to porters who work on their own account and with such hardships.
In fact, they do not receive even a fraction of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) photography fee that, along with the 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) entrance fee, the guards of this reserve charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its mule people.
“This work is for livestock, not for people,” says Badrusin, a 42-year-old stock carrier who has spent three decades on the Kawah Ijen since leaving college.
Able to lift up to 110 kilograms, he assures that he will tolerate work “as much as he can”, because he needs money for the education of his three children aged 18 to 10 years.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here, because a volcano is my whole life.
Although sulfur burns the throat and burns the eyes when the wind suddenly changes and catches miners in dense pillars of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so hardy that none complains of their severe illnesses ... more serious, obviously, than their habitual breathing problems, arthrosis, knee pains and shoulder ulcers that have deformed under the weight of the baskets.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unainik can now only lift 50 kilograms in his 53 years.
Every day, he and his comrades remove 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to a warehouse in Tamansari, covering a distance of 18 kilometers along a narrow path among the thickets.
“I’m not going to retire, I’m going to die here because a volcano is my whole life,” Unainik says, opening his mouth wide, which lacks a few teeth.
Of his five children, the eldest, 30 years old, also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but poverty perpetuates from generation to generation one of the most difficult occupations in the world: what human mules from Kawah Ijen do.
Singapore is looking for children to save the economy
Singaporeans blame career, stress, and housing and education prices for the lack of children.
"The population of Singapore needs to grow."
I am a patriot husband, you are my patriot wife, we will fulfill our civic duty and create life!
It may seem incredible that these lines are part of mint cake ads, but despite this — or perhaps because of this — this video became a YouTube hit in Singapore earlier this year.
These phrases are part of a rap that uses local sayings like "Let's put the bao (bun) in the stove" to make fun of Singapore's birth rate.
The advertising agency that made this video, BBH, hopes that with the help of advertising they will be able to draw attention to this problem in an entertaining way.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the power of music to make people do "their national duty."
This thing is purely for the internet, so we needed to make it fun and funny.
This is the main problem in the country.
We are the worst in the world at reproducing our own kind, so we felt that this is a topic that we should touch upon.
We knew the government was trying to do a lot of things, like launch pheromones or organize quick dating parties (blitz dates).
Many of these ideas may have been creative, but they didn’t necessarily work.
So we thought, why don't we do the most creative thing we can to solve this problem, which is to make a rap?
1.2 children
Those who don’t take it lightly are the Singapore government.
It spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
The state package for couples and parents provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and provides tax breaks.
But all this has low efficiency.
Singapore is a wealthy and high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leadership and its strict public control.
The birth rate in Singapore, according to its National Population Authority, is currently at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was below 2 - what is known as the replacement percentage - was in 1976.
So why don’t Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of the National Population Office’s Couples and Families Policy Branch, says the reason is “improved education” and “a wider range of career opportunities.”
“This has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, in addition to marriage and the creation of a family,” she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to the increase in the number of bachelors and the postponement of marriages and the birth of children, as a result of which the birth rate in Singapore has decreased.
Meanwhile, immigration policies that aim to dramatically increase immigration to counter population decline are causing outrage among the local population.
Singapore has websites where barely hidden xenophobia is rampant against many new immigrants, especially Chinese, who have been criticized for keeping wages low and unwilling to integrate.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons Singapore’s ruling party scored its worst election result since independence last year.
After the election, there was an attempt to solve the problem, with quotas and higher taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While falling birth rates have a known impact on the nation’s economic growth, tax revenues, medical spending, and immigration policies, Singapore’s example is also beginning to have some unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to prevent so many small houses from being built.
For example, it began to affect the real estate sector.
The Urban Development Guide has gone on to control the number of small apartments known as the "shoes box" that can be built in certain areas of the city.
This apartment of 46 square meters is selling very well.
However, there is an opinion that they can contribute to a bachelor lifestyle and deprive the incentive of developers who want to build a large family home.
But Lim Yu Sun, CEO of homebuilder EL Developers, says their shoe boxes are selling much faster than the more spacious ones.
They are more popular, in the sense that such apartments are sold out for several days, even weeks, faster than larger apartments.
As a result, our cash receipts are increasing.
However, he concedes that the new regulations provide clearer guidelines for developers who used to be put on hold if they wanted to offer too many small apartments in the project.
Too tense.
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new rules may be a step in the direction of increasing national fertility, after talking to Singaporeans who work in the financial quarter of the center, it seems that they will not have much effect.
“People are very stressed, housing is expensive, as well as education, and because of this, many people postpone it,” says the young manager.
Other people may have children.
“But it’s important for me to have my own money and time,” says another young man of 20.
Men and women mention their careers, stress, and housing and education prices as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So no matter how hard the government tries to encourage its citizens to have children, the Singaporeans have the final say.
Personal offline - personal online
Confidentiality.
According to the dictionary of the Royal Academy of Spanish, it is a property of private life or “the sphere of personal life, which have the right to protect against any interference”.
What is personal for a minor under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and on social media?
Does he understand the dangers of discussing situations on the Internet that he probably wouldn’t share outside the Internet?
elPeri?dico interviewed five young people between the ages of 10 and 15, who were frequent users of the network.
On four occasions, they associated the term with "something very mine", in the personal plane, and "password and username" when applied to social networks.
“My biggest secrets I wouldn’t upload,” says 10-year-old Jorge, when trying to explain the meaning of personal on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
