On FB I upload beautiful pictures or pictures from games.
I am also having fun with my friends.
“I wouldn’t share a photo that’s not mine, or someone who’s behaving stupidly,” he says.
The boy realizes that it is bad to publish indecent photos of naked people, crimes or write offensive or violent comments.
Jorge says he knows 35 friends he has on FB and nine of his followers on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Mother knows she has a password to one of the accounts.
I started Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
“I don’t know if they answer me, I just download them,” he adds.
“Social media is fun, I can talk to distant relatives or my friends quickly,” he points out.
Without hesitation, he replies that he would never accept a request from a stranger.
I wouldn't consider someone who would recommend him to a stranger.
The case of 14-year-old Jose is different.
This teenager has open accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, and in the latter admits that he does not know 20 people added to his friend list.
“It doesn’t scare me because we have something in common, music, for example,” he points out.
According to the boy, no one to him did not rub into the trust and did not ask for his home address or phone number.
“If I’m pressured or demanded, I’ll just remove them from my account,” he admits.
Jose became a follower of Ask after reading the recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is no stranger to the experience of what is today known as cyber mobbing.
A friend of mine was being blackmailed on a social network.
He was threatened and extorted money.
“He never knew who it was,” he said.
The victim, according to Jose, did not delete the account.
"Just turned on the privacy."
It then explains the sequence of steps to set up an account in a secure way.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yes, I would do that if I didn't like the person or if I wanted to.
"Although I know it's cyber mobbing," he confirms.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and education and training specialist, believes that to guide children and adolescents, it is necessary to understand that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
“The Internet has emerged as a means to find information, but with the advent of these sites, the rules of the game have changed,” she notes.
Porras points out that academic Mark Prenski, a master of pedagogy at Yale University and author of Digital Aboriginals and Immigrants, invented these terms to explain the phenomenon.
Digital aborigines are they, children and young people who were born in the era of technology.
“We’re digital immigrants who have to teach them while we’re still learning ourselves,” she says.
This topic is difficult because we ask them to have a certain criterion of what can or can not be distributed, published or spoken, at an age when maturity is not enough for this.
“Also, they should be selective, while the most important thing for them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences,” she adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to show what privacy is for children and adolescents is to ask questions that make them think.
“Telling them not to do it is useless,” she adds.
Porras then lists some options: there are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why do you do it online?
Or would you like it if you posted a photo of you like the one you posted about your friend?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
When you sign photos from parties, do you ask for permission from other people to mark them?
And one more thing, does everyone need to know what you are doing in every moment?
Another point is to let them know that they have to behave online in the same way they do offline.
The rules are the same.
“Outside of the Internet, a person behaves with respect, responsibility and other principles, the same should be in social networks,” she says.
Vigilance
Estuardo Guardia, a university lecturer, primary education professor and education consultant, explains the need for heads of families to read social media policies in good faith.
Understanding each of the points, they have good reason to talk to children about the prerequisites for opening an account on the Internet.
“For example, age and what is allowed to distribute or publish,” he says.
According to Gaurdius, the key question is to remind children to "don't talk to strangers."
UNASUR Summit ends without the Lima Declaration
The 6th Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the promulgation of the Lima Declaration, previously declared and theoretically signed by seven mandatory participants.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VI ordinary meeting of heads of state and government of UNASUR, but sources from the Office and the presidential administration indicated on the main page that it will be handed over after closing, but then confirmed that at some point it will be published on the website of the Peruvian government.
When asked about the text, they pointed out that the contents had been laid out by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Journalists’ access to information about the Summit was limited all the time.
During the day, only a video of the presidential assembly without a sound was broadcast in the press hall with the message “closed meeting, sound is prohibited”.
Some of the information that circulated among the reporters was relayed by the spokespersons of some of the UNASUR governments present at the meeting, but not the Peruvian one.
The only document circulated throughout the day was a list of participating presidents, which angered hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Subsequently, the administration of the President of Peru sent an electronic message to the media with the “final declaration” of the summit, but we are talking about the statement of Umala, not the official document that ended the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd South American-Arab Summit (ASPA), and at that time, despite the insistence of the press, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had previously been announced, was also not circulated.
On the official ASPA website, you can check that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to provide transmission systems for all journalists, but limited the receipt of information as much as possible.
The summit also ended with a joint decision by Chile and Peru to accept the verdict of the Hague Court, which will settle the territorial dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastien Pinera, gathered at a regional meeting and ratified that they would abide by the decision of the International Court of Justice, which begins on Monday in The Hague hearing statements by both sides, as part of the charge that Lima has brought against Santiago.
"We will abide by and enforce a decision that will clarify the differences we are currently presenting to this international court," Umala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has been, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful resolution of differences, covenants and international tribunals," Piniera added, and welcomed Umala's handshake amid the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by both Presidents that they would obey the International Court of Justice came immediately after Colombia protested this week the Bogota Pact, under which it recognized the subordination of the verdicts of that international court following a decision on maritime borders with Nicaragua that it considered to be erroneous.
The summit was held in the absence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chavez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, whose membership in UNASUR has been suspended since 2011 after the impeachment of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Umala, was responsible for opening the discussions in the morning and closing the summit, just after noon Lima time.
The head of state read the final document, in which he said that 16 agreements were adopted and directions of action for 31 projects among South American countries were approved, the amount of the estimated investment amounted to $ 17 billion.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries will take “important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding residency agreements.”
He said action was being taken to improve “cooperation against citizens’ insecurity and against organized transnational crime, action to increase access to medicines, low-cost Internet access in all corners of South America, and taking into account the combined and effective manner of natural disaster risks.”
As Europe is in crisis, "economic unification (of Latin America) should not have a triumphal basis, but should serve to expand our production base and anticipate a better future for our cities," Umala added.
“We have decided to grant privileges to a group of 31 landmark projects that will improve the connectivity of South America’s spaces, especially in the village and border areas ... bringing our countries together and forming new economic schemes,” he said.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five referred to Peru, and were limited to transverse axes on its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two aimed at greater connectivity with Ecuador, but he did not provide more details.
The final document also touched upon the political situation in Paraguay.
“We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve its re-accession to the Union of South American Nations,” from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of well-being and peace, to be united, and to have good relations among its neighbours, was another theme highlighted at the summit.
In that sense, the Colombian president, Juan Manuel Santos, said before taking part in the regional meeting that he hoped to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico City to negotiate in a respectful manner on a maritime dispute as a result of the verdict of an international court challenged by Bogota.
“The day after tomorrow (Saturday) I may meet with President Daniel Ortega,” Santos said.
“We will review all these ways, they are not mutually exclusive, including the pact with Nicaragua will require discussion with Nicaragua,” he said.
“With President Ortega, I hope I can tell him that we will deal with this in the most civilized and respectful way possible,” Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City, where they are scheduled to attend the inauguration of the country's new president, Enrique Pegna Nieto.
Also within the framework of the summit, the defense ministers of the bloc preliminarily met to approve the Action Plan for 2013, which is aimed at strengthening dialogue and consensus on the protection of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay form UNASUR, although the participation of the latter has been suspended.
Peru has an interim presidency in the regional bloc.
“South America must learn from Europe on integration of citizenship”: Rafael Correa
Ecuador’s president, Rafael Correa, confirmed today that the creation of a common citizenship is the goal in which “South America, in this case, yes, must learn from Europe.”
Correa, who participated in the 6th Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) held in Lima, told state television Peru that Europeans "killed each other during World War II" and other clashes, "but now they are almost the same fatherland."
