In addition, the Ecuadorian President considered “well-founded” the desire of his Colombian counterpart Juan Manuel Santos to negotiate with Nicaragua on maritime borders between the two countries after the decision of the International Court of Justice of The Hague, which turned out to be in favor of Nicaraguan maritime sovereignty.
At the moment, this decision is not respected.
This is a problem between the South American and Central American countries.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the desire to go together.
We need to work them together to overcome them and keep moving forward.
He also expressed hope for a good conclusion to the dispute over maritime boundaries, which is conducted in the same court of Peru and Chile, and said that “it is right for Latin America to apply to international bodies if the two countries undertake to make a decision, no matter how difficult it may be.”
Regarding the opportunity to stand as a candidate in Ecuador’s upcoming presidential election to run for a third consecutive term, he said he viewed the opportunity “with great optimism and joy, although sometimes it’s quite difficult.”
Correa assured that if he lost the elections in February 2013, he would retire from public life.
Personally, I have never been interested in power, but in unfair situations like Ecuador, socio-economic poverty can only be corrected by political power.
“My political movement felt that I was the one who guaranteed this likely victory, so we have to accept this responsibility,” he said.
If I win, that would be my last term as president, and then we're out of public life.
If we lose, the same thing.
“This is a decision,” he confirmed.
Correa also mentioned a new course of treatment for Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez in Cuba.
I just spoke to Venezuelan Vice President Nicolas Maduro, who told me that he went for treatment that was already scheduled, routine, and that he is expected to miss the campaign to return to Cuba.
“This does not mean an aggravation of President Chavez’s state of health,” he explained.
The Ecuadorian head of state took part today in Lima in the 6th Summit of Heads of State and Government of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR), which concluded with calls for greater regional integration to maintain progress, equality and security.
AIDS deaths today are the result of late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 when he was announced that his AIDS test had tested positive.
“I was stunned,” he recalls that difficult moment, despite all the doctor’s tact.
The young man hid it from his family.
Having decided to cope with the disease on his own, he wanted to learn as much as possible about it. And his efforts were justified - he has already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
Fabrizio is one of the "oldest" patients of the HIV department of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he got in 1994, having overcome many obstacles.
He has been living with a diagnosis of human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years. In the early 90s, it would be hard to believe - there were too few treatment options then, too little knew about the disease, too biased towards patients.
So, even the director of the clinic of the Mexican Institute of social protection did not want to say goodbye to him, “because he had a cut.”
In other words, in those days, having AIDS was a sentence.
Now it is possible to survive with this syndrome and do it without compromising the quality of life.
However, not knowing about their illness, still many people come when the virus has already caused damage, “exhausted” their immune system and they suffer from opportunistic infections.
31 years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, at least after the first reported cases, “a big achievement at the moment is that the survival of a patient who starts treatment in a timely manner and the survival of the general population are exactly the same,” said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV department of HCG, referring to the fact that this information was confirmed in April this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Andrade Villanueva, an infectious disease specialist and expert on HIV/AIDS, explained that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is not a sentence, but the duration and quality of life depend on the degree of damage to the immune system available to patients at the beginning of diagnosis, with a better life expectancy for those who do not use drugs: up to 30 years with the number of 200 CD4, and up to 50 years, when 500 CD4 are reported.
Simply put, the above means that anyone who receives an HIV-positive diagnosis at the age of 25, according to these terms, “by maintaining control, will be able to live without problems up to 75 years,” he explained.
To assess this progress, it should be remembered that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is an average of 76 years.
Although mortality has declined significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has fallen from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNAIDS annual report), and it is also true that 60 per cent of patients in the national database have died since the advent of AIDS.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and 187 deaths have already been recorded by May of this year; however, it is claimed that there is widespread access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
Why are there still deaths?
Personally, I don't think the problem is access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's how things are in our hospital.
At least the last 12 years we have not had a shortage of medicines, the problem is that patients come very late, because they do not know about their infected condition, that is, in the late stages of the disease.
“Nine out of ten patients come when they already have some kind of opportunistic infection; what needs to be done to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to be diagnosed at an earlier stage, and therefore it is necessary to provide samples for detection on a mass scale, for all people who ask for it.”
In their proposal, experts and officials of the State Council for AIDS Prevention in Jalisco (COESIDA), as well as patients themselves, like Fabrizio, who turned to a private laboratory for verification, prompted only by the fact that his friend did it and, despite his young age, he was already in the AIDS stage and even suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancer tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they’re going to die and don’t want to know anything.
"If I die anyway, I'd rather nag three times a week," they say. But not in my case.
There are positive changes, I eat well, do exercises, take medications.
To date, his parents only know that he suffered from cancer.
I live a normal life like anyone else.
“I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but with mutual responsibility, I take care of myself and the other person,” Fabrizio, who agreed to share his personal life with MILENIO JALISCO, said in a statement.
Let them check if there was a risk of infection, let them know as soon as possible if they are HIV-positive, so better, and if they already have a diagnosis, let them know that they can live like any other person, being responsible.
This report summarizes the theme of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There are great gaps between health programs and ordinary citizens, says Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has tackled the problem of HIV.
And the biggest is prevention.
In places dedicated to this task, “in fact, increased the distribution of condoms, before we were given one or two, now we are given packages of a hundred, and this is very good, but it turns out that there are those who still do not have access to a condom,” he said.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
"Why do you need them?" is a popular question, with echoes and condemnation from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy staff and health workers, which teenagers do not want to hear, the propagandist assured.
I propose to change this inefficient distribution; that condoms be not only behind the counters and that a hundred of them be in the vending machines in public toilets in places frequented by young people.
This is not to encourage promiscuity.
It’s not about paying for beer and a motel, Governor Emilio Gonzalez replied when asked if it was possible to give out condoms under his leadership.
“It’s not sexuality, it’s best to make condoms available to those who already practice sexual activity,” he said.
Key data in Jalisco
A total of 13,435 cases (12,158 AIDS cases and 1,317 HIV cases) have been reported.
The state ranks 4th in the national ranking for new and cumulative cases of AIDS and 13th for HIV.
92% of infections are sexually transmitted, 6% through the blood and 2% through the perinatal route.
It is estimated that 50,000 people can live with HIV, as there are 4 to 5 people who do not know about it per one registered case.
Given the ratification by the United States Court of Appeals of a decision that annuls the Vitro Group's debt restructuring achieved through competitive proceedings in Mexico, the scenario sets a fateful precedent for any national company with branches in a neighboring country that has solvency problems.
It seems that the procedures in support of the survival of firms that are allowed by Mexican laws are not valid in the country of stripes and stars, contrary to international agreements.
In practical terms, the approval of the June 15 ruling by Judge Harlene Hale in the Northern District of Texas Bankruptcy Court leaves Mexican firms defenseless in the face of the possibility of seizing their property across the Rio Grande.
However, the ruling opens the door to a leading glass manufacturer in Mexico to appeal to the United States Supreme Court, citing three inconsistencies as evidence.
As an introduction, while the judge of the case notes that creditors should be regulated by the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, located in New Orleans, says that the main proceeding concerns a bankruptcy proceeding pending in Mexico.
The first paragraph implies the annulment of international judicial cooperation in cases of insolvency of transnational enterprises.
In fact, for this purpose, the United Nations Model Law on the Unification of International Trade Law was created, defining the American Institute of Law as an arbitrator.
Second, the verdict establishes that without inter-firm voting, recognized in the critical mass of competitive debt production that had before the parent company Vitro branches, would not have achieved the majority required to approve the restructuring.
However, this possibility is recognized by Mexican laws.
In fact, Vitro was not the first time this scheme was adopted.
There are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose intercompany debts were guaranteed by the Federal Institute of Competitive Industries.
It is also true that by subtracting the votes of the affiliates, the Vitro creditors who fought against it in the United States courts, namely vulture funds like Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional, and Liverpool Limited, would not have reached the majority.
The vote would have been 45 percent against 37.
This data is omitted by the Court of Appeal.
On the other hand, he blames Vitro for the difficult situation it has faced since 2008, affected by the severe economic crisis that has overtaken the United States in striking the country.
So far, the firm of the Gonzalez Sada family will appeal the decision to the appellate court itself, so that the vote reached its plenum, that is, five judges, due to the fact that only three voted.
In the event of failure, an application for a certificate will be filed, which will require a review of the proceedings by the highest court, in this case the United States Supreme Court.
Worst of all, the court rejected a document sent by the Mexican government in the role of amicus curiae (“friend of the court”), which describes the process followed by Vitro under the Law on Competitive Proceedings, signaling that it exempts itself from compliance with the agreements signed by both countries to link it to Article 15 of the US Bankruptcy Law.
In addition, it is noted that the country has complied with the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, that is, the rules established for cases of interstate insolvency, which guarantee equality for debtors and creditors.
