Hector "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
Hector "Hetin" Reyes, an avid basketball traveler, has been associated with this sport for more than 60 years and, thanks to him, traveled the whole world.
Few people in Puerto Rico remember as many basketball stories as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
Before his brain hemorrhage tied him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes had been immersed in the sport for more than 60 years, as a small-category player, a Major Basketball League player, a BSN commissioner and leader with the Bayamone Cowboys and president of the Basketball Federation.
“I’ve played many roles in basketball throughout my life, including several at the same time as when I was president of the BSN, CEO of the National Team and president of the federation in the 90s,” Reyes recalls during Primera Hora’s visit to his home in Bayamon, where he lives with Isabelle, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
“Basketball was my life.
Reyes does not exaggerate by making this claim.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photographs and memorabilia collected over his long journey, testify to this.
Bayamon in the Heart
With the greatest emotion, he keeps those who remember his path through the Cowboys, from the mid-50s as a player until 1982, when he turned 15 years old as a co-agent or contract agent.
“These have been my best years, which I have enjoyed the most because I have had the opportunity to be part of eight Cowboys championships since 1967, as an agent, co-agent or leader.
There have been many years of joy, including five championships held from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to one in 1981, the year Jerome Minsey made his BSN debut.
From that moment on, Kuko Ortiz, who was a great administrator, became the head of the company," Reyes said.
I remember Gene Bartow, who was on his way here and was at the University of Alabama, Birmingham, saying to me, "I have a very strong player for you, he's 6'7."
"Want to?"
And that was the beginning of Minsi, one of the best players Puerto Rico had.
Bartow then recommended sniper Raymond Gauss, who gained citizenship and became one of our top scorers.
I remember saying that if Minsey had brought the championship to Bayamone, Gauss would have helped win another one.
I enjoyed the Cowboy Championship with Gauss, but at a distance, because by 1988 I was already listed as the head of the federation.
By that time, I preferred to enjoy his achievements and Minsi’s achievements in the national team.
I remember the first time we won against the United States during the Olympic qualifying tournament in Mexico in 1989.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we got fourth place and it had to be bronze, if not for the Canadian referee who made us replay the final game, Reyes said.
Is that team from the 1990 World Cup the best team you've ever seen?
She is among the best, as well as the one that won the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite was the one from the 1991 Pan-American Games in Cuba, when we won gold and broke the US national team, which was quite similar to the one that won us bronze at the World Cup.
Not only did Minsey, Gauss, Ramon Rivas, Fico Lopez and 'Piculin' (Ortiz) play on that team again, but also young (Havier) 'Tonito' Colon and James Carter, brothers Leon (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario 'Kihote' Morales, who was unable to participate in 90 due to a knee injury.
The team, which may not have been the best in terms of personnel, but brought us a gold medal and great joy, was the team of the 1995 Olympic Qualifying Tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With role players like Canito Nieves, Pablo Alice and young Rolando Hurruitner in return for players suspended for disorder in the Mar del Plata Pan American Championship, we won gold against all predictions.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
Without a doubt, it was Piculin Ortiz.
His performance in international tournaments is impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico dominated at this level the way Piculin did.
And that doesn’t include his career in the various leagues he played in.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
That's a very difficult question.
We had a very good young man, including Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
From a young age, I really like the work of Leo Arilla.
What do you consider to be your main achievement in the federation?
Participation in the most glorious era of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and that in the early 90s BSN had up to 17 teams in the season.
What do you have to do?
There were things that I wanted to implement, such as regionalization of smaller categories.
For example, boys from Ponce play only in their area and only against teams from other parts of the island in the national playoffs.
Now the guys are traveling and playing too much, and it’s unnecessary.
At the very least, I see the fruits of mandatory certification and a course for managers, officials and judges.
It gives me pleasure.
What are you doing now?
Most of all I listen to music, watch music videos of my era on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and occasionally go to basketball games.
And, of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been with me.
Actor Larry Hagman has died.
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931 in Fort Worth, Texas, became world famous for his starring role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R.", in the television series Dallas, in which he embodied a businessman without principles, evil and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the television series Dallas became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in the new season of Dallas, died Friday night due to complications from cancer, according to a family statement provided to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., a Dallas-based production studio.
“Larry is back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, again playing the iconic role he loved the most,” his family said.
Larry’s family and closest friends were with him in Dallas at the Thanksgiving Fair.
Linda Gray, who played the role of his wife in the original series and in the sequel, was next to Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, her spokesman Jeffrey Lane said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, cheerful, affectionate and talented, and I will miss him very much.
"He was an original person and lived a full life," Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992 and admitted to drinking for years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant tumor in the liver and underwent a transplant.
Long before Dallas, Hagman gained fame on television for his role as a decent type in the light comedy "I Dream of Jeannie", broadcast by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive genie girl played by Barbara Eden, and begins to live with her under the same roof.
He was also the main character of two comedies that rarely appeared on the air, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film work included roles well received by critics in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was his masterful interpretation of the delightfully disgusting J.R. that brought Hagman to the pinnacle of fame.
A CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters in its entourage aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The advertising slogan “Who shot J.R.?”, conceived to create a buzz around the episode, full of emotions, in which the character of Hagman is almost killed, gave rise to international discussions and millions of dollars that were risked in bookmakers.
It also helped to attract a record audience to the series at that time.
When the answer was given in the November 1980 episode, an average of 41 million viewers watched it and turned Dallas into the second most watched entertainment program in history, following the 1983 MASH finale, which attracted 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Christine (played by Mary Crosby), who shot him.
J.R. prevented her and then threatened her that he would accuse her of prostitution if she did not get out of town, but others also had reasons to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing as an insatiable corrupt man with a charismatic smile: a dishonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful husband who wanted his alcoholic wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), to be put on treatment.
"I know what should be on the J.R. gravestone," Hagman said in 1988.
It should be said, "Here lies the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
It's the only deal he lost.
Victoria Princeipal, also the heroine of the original series, recalled on Friday Hagman as someone "huge, both on and off the screen."
It is unforgettable and irreplaceable for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of each of us who were lucky enough to know and love it.
Ten episodes of the new release of Dallas were shown a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
The recording of five episodes of the second season has already been completed and the sixth was in production, the channel reported.
Warner or TNT have not yet made a statement about what will happen to the series after Hagman leaves.
A native of Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who shone in classics such as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan".
Martin was still a teenager when she gave birth to him in 1931 during her marriage to lawyer Ben Hagman.
He tried his luck on New York's theater stages in the early 1950s, and then served in the Air Force from 1952 to 1956.
While there, he met and married a young Swedish artist, Mai Axelsson.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and they lived for a long time in the Californian city of Malibu, where many celebrities live.
In 2001, he titled his memoir, Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life.
“I didn’t include anything that I thought would hurt anyone or affect them in any way,” he told Prensa Asociada at the time.
After a liver transplant, he began to promote organ donation and worked as a volunteer in the hospital to help patients experiencing fear.
“I give them advice, I give them courage, I meet them when they go to surgery, and then,” he said in 1996.
I'm trying to offer some comfort, like, "Don't be afraid, it'll be a little uncomfortable for a short time, but you'll be fine."
He also actively opposed smoking and participated in several campaigns.
